Documentation
*************

Introduction
============

   Because PINT is very "intuitive" to use the documentation was
mainly designed as a @{"Online Help" Link "DO_ONLINE"}. It is not necessary to read the whole
documentation. The chapters about the @{"configuration" Link "IN_CONFIG"} should be read
carefully nevertheless.

   This document was created on an Amiga 1200 with Kickstart and
Workbench 3.1.  Because of this it is made especially for the
AmigaGuide Datatype of 3.0/3.1 so some features which are not available
in the normal AmigaGuide for 2.04 or 2.1 are used.

  1. The text style is changed sometimes which ought not be a problem.

  2. Backslashes are escpaped by a second backslash because otherwise
     MultiView will not display them. If you see two backslashes in the
     following example you should halve the number of backslashes in
     your mind while reading this document.

@{b}Test:@{ub} \\


@EndNode

@Node "DO_ONLINE" "PINT.guide/DO_ONLINE"
@Next "DO_DOC"
@Prev "DO_DOC"
@Toc "Main"

Online Help
===========

   PINT features a detailed Online Help which should be able to
explain all questions concerning PINT. That's why you haven't got
to read the whole documentation. If you have a question while using
PINT just press @{b}Help@{ub} and you should get the right help page.

@{i}Attention:@{ui} This documentation must reside in a directory which is part
of AmigaGuide's path.

@{b}Usage:@{ub}

   @{b}*@{ub} To get help concerning a part of the user interface move the mouse
     pointer over the object and press @{b}Help@{ub}. The object's window must be
     the active one to use this feature.

   @{b}*@{ub} If the mouse pointer is not on a certain object you'll get the
     help page for the active window.

   @{b}*@{ub} To get help for a menu item select it with the mouse pointer and
     press @{b}Help@{ub} while holding down the right mouse button.


@EndNode

@Node "IN_INTRO" "PINT.guide/IN_INTRO"
@Next "IN_INSTALL"
@Prev "IN_STARTUP"
@Toc "Main"

Introduction
************

What is PINT?
=============

   PINT is a Mail- and Newsreader for the Universal Message System
(called UMS from now on).

   PINT was especially designed for easy use. The user interface
was created with MUI and complies fully to the Amiga User Interface
Style Guide.  Nearly all functions can be invoked via keyboard
shortcuts to make a fast usage possible.

   This way novices should learn easily how to use PINT and
experts should be able to read mail and news comfortably and efficient.

   Because PINT is not designed for a special network it doesn't
support special network features like Fido file requests. We don't
support such network specific stuff and won't do so in the future.

   For more information about MUI or UMS you should take a look at the
respective documentations distributed with these packages.


@EndNode

@Node "IN_NEW" "PINT.guide/IN_NEW"
@Next "IN_INSTALL"
@Prev "IN_INTRO"
@Toc "Main"

New features in this version
============================

   @{b}v2.1 (24.05.97)@{ub}

   [random order]

   @{b}*@{ub} You can now configure own menus for ARexx scripts for each window, using @{"PINT.RexxMenu" Link "CF_UMS_REXXMENU"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} PINT now @{b}REQUIRES@{ub} @{"NList.mcc" Link "AX_NList"}. Get it from aminet!

   @{b}*@{ub} PINT now scans for, and uses in this order, PINT.#? Reader.#? IntuiNews.#? for @{"configuration" Link "IN_CONFIG"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.Quit" Link "CF_UMS_QUIT"} - Command to be started on exit.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.QuoteSignature" Link "CF_UMS_QSIG"} was missing in the Preference editor.

   @{b}*@{ub} Now it's also possible to configure the group window listview, using @{"PINT.GroupFormat" Link "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.GroupFormat" Link "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"} and @{"PINT.ArticleFormat" Link "CF_UMS_ARTFOR"} listviews, are now @{"NListviews" Link "AX_NList" }.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Separator" Link "CF_UMS_GROUPS"} bugfix.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Address Book Editor" Link "WI_BOOKEDIT"} rewritten as MCC. Now features drag'n'drop and editing of multiple users!

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Preference Editor" Link "WI_PREFSEDIT"} rewritten. Better layout and functionality.

   @{b}*@{ub} The @{"flags" Link "WI_MSG_TEXT"} of a message are now represented by buttons in the message window.

   @{b}*@{ub} Major internal changes. Menusystem rewritten etc.

   @{b}*@{ub} Set old menuitem was mixed up. Fixed.

   @{b}*@{ub} Some bugfixes.

   @{b}*@{ub} Changed values should now be used without restarting, when closing the preference editor.

   @{b}*@{ub} You can now choose the scanmode for a group in the article window, from the article window @{"menu" Link "WI_READ_MENU"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} Minor changes, screentitle etc.

   @{b}v2.0 (16.03.97)@{ub}

   [random order]

   @{b}*@{ub} Intuitive @{"Address Book Editor" Link "WI_BOOKEDIT"} featuring @{"Listtree" Link "AX_LISTTREE"} interface.

   @{b}*@{ub} New @{"addressbook format" Link "CF_UMS_BOOK"} that allowes hiearchic addresses. 
     The old format is still compatible.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Preference Editor" Link "WI_PREFSEDIT"} for easy configuration of PINT.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Separators" Link "CF_UMS_GROUPS"} to split up the Group-list in several parts separated 
     with a header. Configurabe via @{"PINT.Groups" Link "CF_UMS_GROUPS"} for all groups and mails,
     including folders.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"About MUI.." Link "WI_GRP_MENU"}, @{"MUI..." Link "WI_GRP_MENU"} and @{"Iconify..." Link "WI_GRP_MENU"} menuitems added to group window menu.

   @{b}*@{ub} PINT offers a free personal @{"registration" Link "CF_UMS_REG"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Contact Support" Link "WI_GRP_MENU"} updated.

   @{b}*@{ub} Messages written by you are displayed with @{"bold text" Link "WI_ART_LIST"} in article window.

   @{b}*@{ub} Messages addressed to you are displayed with @{"highlite text" Link "WI_ART_LIST"}
     in article window.

   @{b}*@{ub} All @{"flags" Link "WI_MSG_TEXT"} are showed in message window. These can also be toggled.

   @{b}*@{ub} MagicWB, NewIcon and ProLite icons.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Old-flag" Link "WI_READ_MENU"} can now be toggled.

   @{b}*@{ub} Support for CrashMail's @{"audit-request" Link "WI_MAIL_MENU"} and @{"receipt-request" Link "WI_MAIL_MENU"} attribute.
     These are available in the mailmessage menu.

   @{b}*@{ub} The @{"date" Link "WI_ART_LIST"} that the message arrived to your system is displayed 
     in the article window.

   @{b}*@{ub} The @{"date" Link "WI_MSG_TEXT"} that the message arrived to your system, and the @{"date" Link"WI_MSG_TEXT"} that
     the message was written, is displayed in the message window.

   @{b}*@{ub} Some bugfixes.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Forward" Link "WI_READ_MENU"} of a message from Mail to News is now possible.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.DisplayRaw" Link "CF_UMS_RAW"} - Disable attribute processing.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.DisplayBeep" Link "CF_UMS_BEEP"} - Beep if a message is to you.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.QuoteSignature" Link "CF_UMS_QSIG"} - Include signatures in quotes. 

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.Wordwrap" Link "CF_UMS_WRAP"} - Disable wordwrapping.

   @{b}*@{ub} Enhanced Quoting.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.QuoteEmptyLines" Link "CF_UMS_QELINES"} - Don't quote empty lines.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.QuotePostFix" Link "CF_UMS_QPFIX"} - Handle quotes more intelligent.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"NList.mcc" Link "AX_NLIST"} is now used if @{"Mailtext.mcc" Link "AX_MAILTEXT"} is used as @{"PINT.Display" Link "CF_UMS_DISP"}
     This is done to support some new features in @{"Mailtext.mcc" Link "AX_MAILTEXT"} v3.0

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Local rescan" Link "RX_RESCAN"} in article window. Available as a menuoption, and 
     as a REXX command.

   @{b}*@{ub} Two more REXX-events, @{"WRITTEN" Link "CF_UMS_REXX"} and @{"REPLIED" Link "CF_UMS_REXX"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} More REXX-commands;

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"GETMSGNUM" Link "RX_GETMSGNUM"} DISPLAY,WRITTEN/S,REPLIED/S

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"SCANMODE" Link "RX_SCANMODE"} INCMODE/A,ALLMODE/A

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"Global search window" Link "WI_GLOBSEARCH"} can now be used to select messages in the
     article window too. This way you can select on all types of patterns, not just names and subjects.

   @{b}*@{ub} Groupname moved to titlebar in message window.

   @{b}*@{ub} Overall layout improvements in message window.

   @{b}*@{ub} The article list displays the name of the @{"receiver" Link "WI_ART_LIST"}.

   @{b}*@{ub} Bubble help is available for ALL gadgets.

   @{b}*@{ub} You can now search on the @{"exported-flag" Link "WI_GLS_FLAGS"} in the global search window.

   @{b}*@{ub} @{"PINT.ArticleFormat" Link "CF_UMS_ARTFOR"} - Configure article window listview

   @{b}*@{ub} And some minor stuff...

@EndNode

@Node "IN_INSTALL" "PINT.guide/IN_INSTALL"
@Next "IN_UPGRADE"
@Prev "IN_NEW"
@Toc "Main"

Installation
============

   There are some requirements for the installation of PINT. The
used machine should fulfill the following hardware and software
requirements:

   @{b}*@{ub} Installed UMS package 11.5beta or newer

   @{b}*@{ub} Installed MUI system version 3.3 or newer

   @{b}*@{ub} NList.mcc v0.47 or newer

Recommended:

   @{b}*@{ub} Mailtext.mcc v3.0 or newer

   @{b}*@{ub} Operating system 3.0 or newer

   @{b}*@{ub} 2MB or more free FastRAM. This is not only a fault by PINT,
     MUI and UMS take their part of the main memory, too. If you are
     really low on memory reduce the buffers specified in the UMS
     configuration. This will reduce the performance of the whole
     Newssystem but may help to get PINT to work with less that
     2MB RAM. @{i}Attention:@{ui} PINT will terminate automatically in low
     memory situations, no special error message will be returned.

   @{b}*@{ub} A fast CPU is not required but will increase comfort a lot.

You have to do the following steps for the manual installion of
PINT:

   @{b}*@{ub} Copy the files "PINT" and "PINT.info" into a directory
     which is in the command path of the shell or where they can be
     easily accessed from the Workbench.

   @{b}*@{ub} The editor which will be used for creating the messages can be set
     up in two different ways. Either you can set the environment
     variable @{"EDITOR" Link "CF_ENV_EDITOR"} to your editor's command (e.g. "TTX WAIT" for
     TurboText or "ED -sticky" for CED) or you use the corresponding
     UMS config variable (see @{"PINT.Editor" Link "CF_UMS_EDITOR"}).

   @{b}*@{ub} Copy the address book file "PINT.Addresses" into any
     directory and set the UMS config variable @{"PINT.Book" Link "CF_UMS_BOOK"} to it,
     the default is the current directory at PINT's startup.

   @{b}*@{ub} The documentation "PINT.guide" should be copied into a
     directory which is part of AmigaGuide's path. Under OS 3.0 you
     should use the directory "Help:english/" for this purpose. This
     file is used for the @{"Online Help" Link "DO_ONLINE"} of PINT, too.

@EndNode

@Node "IN_UPGRADE" "PINT.guide/IN_UPGRADE"
@Next "IN_STARTUP"
@Prev "IN_INSTALL"
@Toc "Main"

How to update your configuration
================================

   Since PINT is based on the source of @{"IntuiNews" Link "AX_CREDITS"}, most variables
and behaviours are the same. To update your old configuration from IntuiNews to
work with, and take advantage of all new features in PINT, just follow these 
simple steps:

   @{b}*@{ub} Rename all variables in ums.config from IntuiNews.#? to PINT.#?

   @{b}*@{ub} Do a simular rename in ENVARC:MUI/ with all files concerning 
     IntuiNews.

   @{b}*@{ub} PINT uses the extension .pint for it's rexx scripts.
     You should rename your current scripts, or use the supplied ones.

   @{b}*@{ub} PINT.Addresses is the default for @{"PINT.Book" Link "CF_UMS_BOOK"}
     You may have to change this.

   @{b}*@{ub} Reboot.

   @{b}*@{ub} Try starting PINT. If the screenmode isn't what it should be,
     you have to update that in MUI and PSI.

   @{b}*@{ub} Read about all @{"new features" Link "IN_NEW"} in PINT. Try them out!

   @{b}*@{ub} If you like PINT and want to use it, please consider using the 
     @{"Free Registration" Link "BI_REG"} feature. This will support @{"us" Link "BI_AUTHORS"} in making @{"future" Link "AX_FUTURE"} versions.

   @{b}*@{ub} Have fun! =)

@Endnode

@Node "IN_CONFIG" "PINT.guide/IN_CONFIG"
@Next "IN_STARTUP"
@Prev "IN_UPGRADE"
@Toc "Main"

Configuration
=============

   PINT's setup is mainly controlled by UMS configuration
variables. Only the editor can be set up via an environment variable.


Environment variables
 @{" EDITOR " Link "CF_ENV_EDITOR"} 

UMS Configuration variables:

   Applications using UMS have the possibility to access their own
variables in the main UMS configuration file. This file is located in
the same directory as the messagebase. Because PINT makes heavy
use of this feature it does not require an own configuration file.

   For a simple configuration you should use the ConfUMS package,
or the integrated PINT prefseditor.

   If a variable has the suffix "[...]" you can expand its name by a
full or particular group name. The dot in the group name is used as
seperator. The variable "PINT.Signature.comp.sys.amiga = ..." e.g.
would apply to all UseNet-Amiga-Groups. This method is also explained
by examples for all variables supporting this feature.

   "Misc" is the virtual name for the group created by a global search
through the messagebase.

   The group name "Mail" applies to personal mail. You can expand it by
a folder's name. With "PINT.Signature.Mail.MailingList = ..." e.g.
the signature for the folder called "MailingList" is set. If you append
a dot but no folder name the variable is used for your normal personal
mail not located in any folder.

   PINT will scan, and use, variables in this order;

1. PINT.#?
2. Reader.#?
3. IntuiNews.#?

   This means that Reader.QuoteMode.fidonet will be used instead of
PINT.QuoteMode, if both exists.

@{b}Global@{ub} configurations variables:

 @{" PINT.Book           " Link "CF_UMS_BOOK"}		Address book file
 @{" PINT.DontTouch      " Link "CF_UMS_DONT"}		Internal variable for cache
 @{" PINT.FastScan       " Link "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"}		Faster scan of the grouplist
 @{" PINT.GroupFormat    " Link "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"}		Format of listview in the group window
 @{" PINT.Groups         " Link "CF_UMS_GROUPS"}		Groupfilter
 @{" PINT.Moderated      " Link "CF_UMS_MOD"}		Moderated groups
 @{" PINT.Quit           " Link "CF_UMS_QUIT"}		Command to be started on exit
 @{" PINT.Registration   " Link "CF_UMS_REG"}		Your personal registration-code
 @{" PINT.Rexx           " Link "CF_UMS_REXX"}		Starting ARexx-Scripts
 @{" PINT.RexxMenu       " Link "CF_UMS_REXXMENU"}		Config of rexxmenus
 @{" PINT.ScanMode1      " Link "CF_UMS_SCANMODE1"}		Preset of cycle gadget 1
 @{" PINT.ScanMode2      " Link "CF_UMS_SCANMODE2"}		Preset of cycle gadget 2
 @{" PINT.ScanJunked     " Link "CF_UMS_SCANJUNK"}		Scan junked messages
 @{" PINT.Stack          " Link "CF_UMS_STACK"}		Stack for editor call
 @{" PINT.Startup        " Link "CF_UMS_STARTUP"}		Command to be started on startup
 @{" PINT.StartupNew     " Link "CF_UMS_STARTUPN"}		Command to be started on startup
 @{" PINT.TempDir        " Link "CF_UMS_TMPDIR"}		Directory for temporary files
 @{" PINT.Window         " Link "CF_UMS_WINDOW"}		Window definition for standard output

Configuration variables, optional @{b}for each group@{ub}:

 @{" PINT.AnswerTo       " Link "CF_UMS_ANSTO"}		Group for answers
 @{" PINT.ArticleFormat  " Link "CF_UMS_ARTFOR"}		Format of listview in article window
 @{" PINT.Attributes     " Link "CF_UMS_ATTRIB"}		Default Attributes for a message
 @{" PINT.DisableCatchup " Link "CF_UMS_DISC"}		Disable Catchup function
 @{" PINT.Display        " Link "CF_UMS_DISP"}		Configure message display
 @{" PINT.DisplayBeep    " Link "CF_UMS_BEEP"}		Beep if a message is to you
 @{" PINT.DisplayRaw     " Link "CF_UMS_RAW"}		Disable attribute processing
 @{" PINT.Dist           " Link "CF_UMS_DIST"}		Distribution of your messages
 @{" PINT.Editor         " Link "CF_UMS_EDITOR"}		Editor for writing messages
 @{" PINT.Fortune        " Link "CF_UMS_FORTUNE"}		Program for appending cookies
 @{" PINT.ForwardHeader  " Link "CF_UMS_FWDHD"}		Header for forwarded messages
 @{" PINT.FupTo          " Link "CF_UMS_FUPTO"}		Default for FollowUp-To
 @{" PINT.GroupFormat    " Link "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"}		Format of listview in group window
 @{" PINT.Headers        " Link "CF_UMS_HEADERS"}		Header on/off
 @{" PINT.Newsreader     " Link "CF_UMS_NEWSRDR"}		Write newsreader into message header
 @{" PINT.Organization   " Link "CF_UMS_ORG"}		Default for Organization
 @{" PINT.QuoteChars     " Link "CF_UMS_QCHARS"}		Quotecharacters for highlighting messages
 @{" PINT.QuoteEmptyLines" Link "CF_UMS_QELINES"}		Quote empty lines as well as text
 @{" PINT.QuoteHeader    " Link "CF_UMS_QHEADER"}		Header for replies
 @{" PINT.QuoteMode      " Link "CF_UMS_QMODE"}		Preset for Quote Mode
 @{" PINT.QuotePostFix   " Link "CF_UMS_QPFIX"}		Quotestring if already quoted
 @{" PINT.QuoteSignature " Link "CF_UMS_QSIG"}		Include signature in quote
 @{" PINT.QuoteString    " Link "CF_UMS_QSTRING"}		Quotestring for replies
 @{" PINT.QuoteWidth     " Link "CF_UMS_QWIDTH"}		Width of quotes
 @{" PINT.ReplyPrefix    " Link "CF_UMS_REPLPRE"}		Put "Re:" in front of subject ?
 @{" PINT.ReplyTo        " Link "CF_UMS_REPLYTO"}		Default for Reply-To
 @{" PINT.SaveDrawer     " Link "CF_UMS_SAVEDRW"}		Directory for saving messages
 @{" PINT.SaveMark       " Link "CF_UMS_SAVEMARK"}		Seperator between save messages.
 @{" PINT.SaveNameType   " Link "CF_UMS_SAVNT"}		Type of the filename for saving
 @{" PINT.Signature      " Link "CF_UMS_SIGNATURE"}		Signature
 @{" PINT.Sort           " Link "CF_UMS_SORT"}		Default sort method for articlelist
 @{" PINT.Wordwrap       " Link "CF_UMS_WRAP"}		Disable wordwrap


@EndNode

@Node "CF_ENV_EDITOR" "PINT.guide/CF_ENV_EDITOR"
@Next "CF_UMS_BOOK"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SORT"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

$EDITOR
=======

   This variable can be used to set the editor used by PINT for
writing or editing messages.

   @{i}Attention:@{ui} PINT requires a standard Amiga texteditor. Lines must
be terminated with a LF ($0A). PINT does @{b}not@{ub} apply any changes to
the textfile before writing it into the messagebase.

   The editor @{b}must not@{ub} detach from CLI. Most editors need a special
option for this behaviour.

   You can set environment variables with the CLI command "SetEnv".

   Try e.g. this command:

     SetEnv EDITOR "ED -sticky"

   to use CED.

   After this use:

     Copy ENV:EDITOR TO ENVARC:

   to save the variable permanently.

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.Editor" Link "CF_UMS_EDITOR"} @{"PINT.Stack" Link "CF_UMS_STACK"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_BOOK" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_BOOK"
@Next "CF_UMS_DONT"
@Prev "CF_ENV_EDITOR"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Book
=========

   PINT supports an address book for saving e-mail addresses of
friends and other important people. The address book is read from a
file and this variable contains the complete filename of it.

   You can use an ARexx script to create an address book at runtime of
PINT. If the value of the variable PINT.Book begins with a "!"
the rest of the string will be used as a name of an ARexx script. This
Arexx script can now use external address book programs to retrieve
email addresses from them and can build up an address book for
PINT.

   The ARexx script is called with the parameter "QUERY" if a new
address book should be build and with the parameters "ADD
<Name>,<Address>,<comment>" if a new address should be stored in the
external address book program.

   The first line in the book is a version string. The current book-version 
is 11 and the first line is therefor "$VER: 11".

@{b}NOTE!@{ub}
   Old book-files are still compatible and is recogniced through lack of 
version-string.

LIST is used instead of GROUP and a new row containing the group's name have
been inserted after the LIST keyword.

@{b}Hiearchic groups are saved in the following format:@{ub}

GROUP
<name>
<comment>

... subgroups contents ...

ENDGROUP

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Complete filename for the address book file:
       ( PINT.Book "UMS:PINT.Addresses" )
     
     Read the address book via an ARexx script:
       ( PINT.Book "!DFA.pint" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} PINT.Addresses (in the current directory)

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Address Book" Link "WI_BOOK"} @{"Rexx: ADD" Link "RX_ADD"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_DONT" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_DONT"
@Next "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"
@Prev "CF_UMS_BOOK"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.DontTouch
==============

This is an internal variable used to hold the group cache.

Don't edit this by hand. Use the desired @{"menus" Link "WI_GRP_MENU"}.

@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"
@Next "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"
@Prev "CF_UMS_DONT"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.FastScan
=============

   If you work with PINT on a slow computer or on an extremely
large messagebase the grouplist scan will take quite a long time. In
this case this flag may help you. If you turn it on PINT doesn't
scan informations about selected, archived, filtered, parked or
postponed messages nor which message are from or to the user. As a
result of this the cycle gadget "ScanMode1" is disabled. You must set
this flag to "Yes" to turn it on. Everything else will be treated as no.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

       Switch fast groupscan on:
         ( PINT.FastScan Yes )

@{b}Default:@{ub} No

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"ScanMode1" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_GRPFOR" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_GRPFOR"
@Next "CF_UMS_GROUPS"
@Prev "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.GroupFormat[...]
=====================

   Using this variable you can configure the listview in the 
group window.

   To define how many columns should be displayed and how they 
should be formatted, you specify a format string.

   This format string must contain one entry for each column
you want to see. Entries are seperated by commas, one entry is 
parsed via dos.library/ReadArgs().

The template for a single entry looks like this:

DELTA=D/N,PREPARSE=P/K,WEIGHT=W/N,
MINWIDTH=MIW/N,MAXWIDTH=MAW/N,COL=C/N,BAR/S

@{b}DELTA@{ub}
   Space in pixel between this column and the next.
   the last displayed column ignores this setting.
   Defaults to 4.

@{b}PREPARSE@{ub}
   A preparse value for this column. Setting this
   e.g. to "\33c" would make the column centered.
   See MUIA_Text_Contents for other control codes.

@{b}WEIGHT@{ub}
   The weight of the column. As with MUI's group
   class, columns are layouted with a minimum
   size, a maximum size and weight. A column with
   a weight of 200 would gain twice the space than
   a column with a weight of 100.
   Defaults to 100.

@{b}MINWIDTH@{ub}
   Minimum percentage width for the current column.
   If your list is 200 pixel wide and you set this
   to 25, your column will at least be 50 pixel.
   The special value -1 for this parameter means that
   the minimum width is as wide as the widest entry in
   this column. This ensures that every entry will be
   completely visible (as long as the list is wide enough).
   Defaults to -1.

@{b}MAXWIDTH@{ub}
   Maximum percentage width for the current column.
   If your list is 200 pixel wide and you set this
   to 25, your column will not be wider as 50 pixel.
   The special value -1 for this parameter means that
   the maximum width is as wide as the widest entry in
   this column.
   Defaults to -1.

@{b}COL@{ub}
   This value adjusts the number of the current column.
   This allows you to adjust the order of your columns
   without having to change your display hook. See
   example for details.
   Defaults to current entry number (0,1,...)

@{b}BAR@{ub}
   Since muimaster.library V11, you can enable a
   vertical bar between this and the next column by
   using this switch.

   If your list object gets so small there is not enough
   place for the minwidth of a column, this column will
   be hidden completely and the remaining space is
   distributed between the remaining columns. This is not
   true if the column is the first column, in this case
   the entries will simply be clipped.

Format
------

   Whenever MUI prints strings, they may contain some special
character sequences defining format, color and style of the text.

'\n'	   Start a new line. With this character you can e.g. create
         multi line buttons.

ESC -    Disable text engine, following chars will be printed
         without further parsing.

ESC u    Set the soft style to underline.

ESC b    Set the soft style to bold.

ESC i    Set the soft style to italic.

ESC n    Set the soft style back to normal.

ESC <n>  Use pen number n (2..9) as front pen. n must be a valid
         DrawInfo pen as specified in "intuition/screens.h".

ESC c    Center current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC r    Right justify current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC l    Left justify current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

@{b}Default:@{ub} "MIW=0 MAW=100 D=16 ,P=\33r D=16,P=\33r"

@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_GROUPS" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_GROUPS"
@Next "CF_UMS_MOD"
@Prev "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Groups
===========

   Some UMS importers create so called "crosspostings" if a message is
part of multiple newsgroups. As a result of this PINT will show a
lot of groups which you don't want to read. With this variable you can
tell PINT which groups you want to see in the grouplist. All
groups not matching the supplied AmigaDOS pattern will not be shown. A
multiline pattern is supported, too.

@{b}Group Separators@{ub}

It's possible to split up the Group-list in several parts separated with a
header. Each line beginning with a '-' is considered a separator.

A double click on a separator will open an article-window containing messages
from all groups between the separator and the next separator (or the end of 
the list). Of course, the ScanModes will be used on each group. (eg selecting 
"Last 25" and opening a separator will yield a list containing the last 25 
messages from each group)

@{b}Mail Separators@{ub}

The mail-folders in the group-list is also possible to hide and sort through
"PINT.Groups" as any ordinary group. Mail is matched as "Mail:Folder"

"Mail" will match unfoldered Mails.
"Mail#?" will match any Mail-folder.
"Mail:Amiga#?" will match all folders beginning with "Amiga".

   The groups in the grouplist will be sorted in the
same order as they appear in this variable.

   @{i}Attention:@{ui} Be careful with this variable because you can easily hide
groups AND mails which you actually want to see.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Show only FidoNet groups:
       ( PINT.Groups "fidonet.#?" )
     
     Show all fidonet groups, all german Amiga groups and de.comm.software.ums:
       ( PINT.Groups
           "fidonet.#?\n"
           "de.comp.sys.amiga.#?\n"
           "de.comm.software.ums\n"
       )

     Show all mail, followed by a separator "Mailinglists" and all folders 
     beginning with list#?. Then a separator, "Fidonet groups", and all 
     fidonet groups:

       ( PINT.Groups
           "Mail\n"
           "-Mailinglists\n"
           "Mail:list#?\n"
           "-Fidonet groups\n"
           "fidonet.#?\n"
       )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "#?" (all groups are shown)

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Groupfilter active" Link "WI_GRP_MENU"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_MOD" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_MOD"
@Next "CF_UMS_QUIT"
@Prev "CF_UMS_GROUPS"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Moderated
==============

   This variable defines in which groups are moderated so that no
messages may be directly written into them. Messages will be converted
into a mail and sent to the moderator.

     All messages written to comp.sys.amiga.announce are send to
     "announce@cs.ucdavis.edu", all messages in
     comp.unix.bsd.netbsd.announce to
     "netbsd-announce-request@agate.berkeley.edu":
     ( PINT.Moderated
         "comp.sys.amiga.announce       Dan Zerkle,announce@cs.ucdavis.edu\\n"
         "comp.unix.bsd.netbsd.announce netbsd-announce-request@agate.berkeley.edu"
     )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (no moderated groups)

@Node "CF_UMS_QUIT" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QUIT"
@Next "CF_UMS_REG"
@Prev "CF_UMS_MOD"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Quit
=========

   You can use this varible to define one or more programs that should
be started on the exit of PINT. 

   The output of the programs appear in the CLI window from which
PINT is started if it's started from the CLI. Otherwise the output
is redirected to a window, defined with the variable @{"PINT.Window" Link "CF_UMS_WINDOW"}.

   The following format identifiers are supported:

     "%a" for 'NAME "<User>" PASSWORD "<Password>" SERVER "<Server>"'
     "%p" for "<Password>"
     "%r" for "<ARexx-Port>"
     "%s" for "<Server>"
     "%u" for "<User>"

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Different commands are called at the exit of PINT:
       ( PINT.Quit
           "sumsset %u %p \"FromName = *\"Magnus Heino*\"\" Selected\n"
           "sumsset %u %p \"FromName = *\"David Rydh*\"\" Selected\n"
       )

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.Window" Link "CF_UMS_WINDOW"}

@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_REG" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_REG"
@Next "CF_UMS_REXX"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QUIT"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Registration
=================

Enter your personal code here to become a fully registred user of PINT.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     ( PINT.Registration "MY_PERSONAL_CODE" )

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"How to register" Link "BI_REG"}

@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_REXX" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_REXX"
@Next "CF_UMS_REXXMENU"
@Prev "CF_UMS_REG"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Rexx
=========

   With this variable you can define various ARexx commands and scripts
which will be executed at different events.

   The variable has the following syntax:

     ( PINT.Rexx
         "OBJECT EVENT COMMAND\\n"
         "..."
         "OBJECT EVENT COMMAND"
     )

@{b}OBJECT@{ub}
     Defines the Object on which the event is focused. The following
     values will be accepted:

        @{b}*@{ub} GROUPWINDOW

        @{b}*@{ub} ARTICLEWINDOW

        @{b}*@{ub} MESSAGEWINDOW

        @{b}*@{ub} MESSAGE

@{b}EVENT@{ub}
     The event for which PINT waits. The following values are
     valid:

        @{b}*@{ub} F1 to F10 - Function key is pressed.

        @{b}*@{ub} DISPLAY - Message is displayed.

        @{b}*@{ub} WRITTEN - This event occurs whenever the user has written 
          and sent a message. The msgid can be retrieved with "GETMSGNUM WRITTEN".

        @{b}*@{ub} REPLIED - This event occurs whenever the user has replied to 
          a message. The msgid of the message which was replied to can be 
          retrieved with "GETMSGNUM REPLIED" and the msgid of the newly 
          written message with "GETMSGNUM WRITTEN".


     ARexx scripts which are started with a function key are called
     asynchron.  This means that the script is started in the
     background and PINT doesn't wait for it to finish.

@{b}COMMAND@{ub}
     Command to be executed

@{b}Example:@{ub}

         ( PINT.Rexx
             "#?Window                F1       ConfUMS.pint\\n"
             "(Article|Message)Window F2       UUDecode.pint Work:Inbound\\n"
             "Message                 DISPLAY  PGPAutoDecrypt.pint"
         )

   With the above configuration PINT will:

   @{b}*@{ub} start the ARexx script ConfUMS.pint if F1 is pressed in one of the
     three windows (Group, Article, Message).

   @{b}*@{ub} start the ARexx script UUDecode.pint with parameter "Work:Inbound"
     if F2 is pressed in the Article- or Message window.

   @{b}*@{ub} start the ARexx script PGPAutoDecrypt.pint if a new message is
     displayed in the Message window.

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"ARexx interface" Link "RX_REXX"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_REXXMENU" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_REXXMENU"
@Next "CF_UMS_SCANMODE1"
@Prev "CF_UMS_REXX"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.RexxMenu
=============

   With this variable you can define different menus for each window,
containing ARexxscripts.

   The variable has the following syntax:

     ( PINT.RexxMenu
         "OBJECTS COMMAND/DRAWER TITLE\\n"
         "..."
         "OBJECTS COMMAND/DRAWER TITLE\\n"
     )

@{b}OBJECT@{ub}
     Defines the window that will use this menu. The following values 
     will be accepted (and all valid AmigaDOS patterns):

        @{b}*@{ub} GROUP

        @{b}*@{ub} ARTICLE

        @{b}*@{ub} MESSAGE

@{b}COMMAND/DRAWER@{ub}
     The path to the command, or drawer contating the script. If a 
     drawer is given, this will be scanned for all #?.pint scripts.

     ARexx scripts which are started with a are called asynchron.  
     This means that the script is started in the background and 
     PINT doesn't wait for it to finish.

     "-" is used to create a separator.

@{b}TITLE@{ub}
     Title of the entry in the menu. If not given, the filename of the
     script will be used instead (the extension is stripped).

@{b}Example:@{ub}

         ( PINT.RexxMenu
             "GROUP                ums:rexx/\\n"
             "(ARTICLE|MESSAGE) \\"ums:rexx/UUDecode.pint t:\\" \\"Decode UU\\"\\n"
             "#?                -\\n"
             "#?                \\"ums:rexx/SetScanMode.pint All Forward\\" \\"ScanMode Forward\\"\\n"
             "#?                \\"ums:rexx/SetScanMode.pint All Backward\\" \\"ScanMode Backward\\"\\n"
         )

NOTE the use of "\\"!!!

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"ARexx interface" Link "RX_REXX"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SCANMODE1" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SCANMODE1"
@Next "CF_UMS_SCANMODE2"
@Prev "CF_UMS_REXXMENU"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.ScanMode1
==============

   PINT supports various methods for selecting messages. This
variable controls the method active at startup time.

   This variable has no effect, if @{"PINT.FastScan" Link "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"} is set to "Yes".

@{b}You should set this variable to one of these values:@{ub}

    @{b}Normal@{ub}
          All messages are scanned.

    @{b}Selected@{ub}
          All pre-selected messages are scanned.

    @{b}PostPoned@{ub}
          All postponed messages are scanned. This value is not very
          useful as default because all postponed message are marked as
          new at startup time.

    @{b}Archived@{ub}
          All archived messages are scanned.

    @{b}Junked@{ub}
          All junked messages are scanned.

    @{b}FromUser@{ub}
          All messages addressed to the current user are scanned.

    @{b}ToUser@{ub}
          All messages written by the current user are scanned.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Show all selected messages after startup:
       ( PINT.ScanMode1 Selected )
     
     Show all archived messages:
       ( PINT.ScanMode1 Archived )

@{b}Default:@{ub} Normal

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.ScanMode2" Link "CF_UMS_SCANMODE2"} @{"ScanMode1" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"} @{"PINT.FastScan" Link "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SCANMODE2" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SCANMODE2"
@Next "CF_UMS_SCANJUNK"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SCANMODE1"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.ScanMode2
==============

   PINT supports various criteria for scanning messages. This
variable contains the one active at startup time.

@{b}You should set this variable to one of these values:@{ub}

    @{b}New@{ub}
          All new messages are scanned.

    @{b}All@{ub}
          All messages are scanned.

    @{b}Last 250@{ub}
          The last 250 messages are scanned.

    @{b}Last 100@{ub}
          The last 100 messages are scanned.

    @{b}Last 50@{ub}
          The last 50 messages are scanned.

    @{b}Last 25@{ub}
          The last 25 messages are scanned.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Show all messages after starting PINT:
       ( PINT.ScanMode2 All )
     
     Scan the last 100 messages:
       ( PINT.ScanMode2 "Last 100" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} New

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.ScanMode1" Link "CF_UMS_SCANMODE1"} @{"ScanMode2" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SCANJUNK" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SCANJUNK"
@Next "CF_UMS_STACK"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SCANMODE2"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.ScanJunked
===============

   Normally PINT ignores filtered messages. This behaviour may be
changed by a menu item. This variable controls the default behaviour.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Scan junked messages:
       ( PINT.ScanJunked Yes )

@{b}Default:@{ub} No

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Scan junked" Link "WI_GRP_MENU"} @{"ScanMode1" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_STACK" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_STACK"
@Next "CF_UMS_STARTUP"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SCANJUNK"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Stack
==========

   PINT normally uses 16384 bytes of stack for calling the editor.
If this amount is not enough you may increase it with this variable.
The minimum value is 4000 bytes.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Set higher stack for Editor:
       ( PINT.Stack 65536 )

@{b}Default:@{ub} 16384

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"EDITOR" Link "CF_ENV_EDITOR"} @{"PINT.Editor" Link "CF_UMS_EDITOR"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_STARTUP" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_STARTUP"
@Next "CF_UMS_STARTUPN"
@Prev "CF_UMS_STACK"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Startup
============

   You can use this varible to define one or more programs that should
be started on the startup of PINT. If you select "Rescan all" in
the Group-Window the programs are called, too.

   The output of the programs appear in the CLI window from which
PINT is started if it's started from the CLI. Otherwise the output
is redirected to a window, defined with the variable @{"PINT.Window" Link "CF_UMS_WINDOW"}.

   The following format identifiers are supported:

     "%a" for 'NAME "<User>" PASSWORD "<Password>" SERVER "<Server>"'
     "%p" for "<Password>"
     "%r" for "<ARexx-Port>"
     "%s" for "<Server>"
     "%u" for "<User>"

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Different commands are called at the startup of PINT:
       ( PINT.Startup
           "sumsset %u %p \"FromName = *\"Magnus Heino*\"\" Selected\n"
           "sumsset %u %p \"FromName = *\"David Rydh*\"\" Selected\n"
       )

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.StartupNew" Link "CF_UMS_STARTUPN"} @{"PINT.Window" Link "CF_UMS_WINDOW"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_STARTUPN" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_STARTUPN"
@Next "CF_UMS_TMPDIR"
@Prev "CF_UMS_STARTUP"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.StartupNew
===============

   This variable has exactly the same syntax as the
@{"PINT.Startup" Link "CF_UMS_STARTUP"} variable. The only difference is that the
specified programs are only called if there are @{i}new@{ui} messages.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Call different commands on startup if new messages have arrived:
       ( PINT.StartupNew
           "SetFolder %a QUIET\\n"
           "Rexx:UMS/mlist2folder.rexx %u %p"
       )

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.Startup" Link "CF_UMS_STARTUP"} @{"PINT.Window" Link "CF_UMS_WINDOW"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_TMPDIR" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_TMPDIR"
@Next "CF_UMS_WINDOW"
@Prev "CF_UMS_STARTUPN"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.TempDir
============

   With this variable you can define the directory for temporary files.
For example PINT puts the file with the messagetext there.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Write all temporary files to hard disk:
       ( PINT.TempDir "Work:T" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "T:"


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_WINDOW" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_WINDOW"
@Next "CF_UMS_ANSTO"
@Prev "CF_UMS_TMPDIR"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Window
===========

   If PINT is started from Workbench this variable defines the
standard output device for external programs. If PINT is started
from CLI the output appears in its CLI window.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     New definition for output window:
       ( PINT.Window "CNC:0/11/640/200/IN_stdout/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "CON:0/16/640/128/PINT/AUTO/CLOSE/WAIT"

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.Startup" Link "CF_UMS_STARTUP"} @{"PINT.StartupNew" Link "CF_UMS_STARTUPN"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_ANSTO" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_ANSTO"
@Next "CF_UMS_ARTFOR"
@Prev "CF_UMS_WINDOW"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.AnswerTo[...]
==================

   This variable is used to redirect the answers to articles in a
certain group into another group. Unlike @{"PINT.FupTo" Link "CF_UMS_FUPTO"} this variable
is applied to your message, not to the next answer. This works with mail
folders, too. In this case you can use @{b}%a@{ub} as a synonym for the original
author.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Answers to articles in "comp.binaries.amiga" to "comp.sys.amiga.misc":
       ( PINT.AnswerTo.comp.binaries.amiga.amigaos "comp.sys.amiga.misc" )
     
     Answers to messages in folder NetBSD directly to the mailing list:
       ( PINT.AnswerTo.Mail.NetBSD "NetBSD Amiga,amiga@NetBSD.org" )
     
     Answers to messages in folder PINT to the original author with a
     copy to "PINT@pixar.owl.de":
         ( PINT.AnswerTo.Mail.PINT
             "%a\n"
             "PINT Support,PINT@pixar.owl.de"
         )

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.FupTo" Link "CF_UMS_FUPTO"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_ARTFOR" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_ARTFOR"
@Next "CF_UMS_ATTRIB"
@Prev "CF_UMS_ANSTO"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.ArticleFormat[...]
=======================

   Using this variable you can configure the listview in the 
article window.

   To define how many columns should be displayed and how they 
should be formatted, you specify a format string.

   This format string must contain one entry for each column
you want to see. Entries are seperated by commas, one entry is 
parsed via dos.library/ReadArgs().

   The template for a single entry looks like this:

DELTA=D/N,PREPARSE=P/K,COL=C/N,BAR/S,TBAR/S,
WEIGHT=W/N,MINWIDTH=MIW/N,MAXWIDTH=MAW/N,
COLWIDTH=CW/N,MINCOLWIDTH=MICW/N,MAXCOLWIDTH=MACW/N,
PIXWIDTH=PW/N,MINPIXWIDTH=MIPW/N,MAXPIXWIDTH=MAPW/N

@{b}DELTA@{ub}
   Space in pixel between this column and the next.
   the last displayed column ignores this setting.
   Defaults to 4.

@{b}PREPARSE@{ub}
   A preparse string for this column.

@{b}COL@{ub}
   This value adjusts the number of the current column.
   Defaults to current entry number (0,1,...)

@{b}BAR@{ub}
   Will draw a vertical bar between this and the next column.

@{b}WEIGHT@{ub}
   The weight of the column. As for MUI's group.

@{b}MINWIDTH@{ub}
   Minimum percentage of the list width for the current column.

@{b}MAXWIDTH@{ub}
   Maximum percentage of the list width for the current column.

@{b}TBAR@{ub}
   Will draw a vertical bar between this and the next column
   but only in the title (ignored if BAR is set).

@{b}COLWIDTH@{ub}
   Wanted number of chars for the current column.
   You will get as PIXWIDTH with number*font_with.
   Possibly more than number chars will fit in the
   column if you use proportional font, anyway you
   are sure than number non italic chars will fit.

@{b}MINCOLWIDTH@{ub}
   Minimum number of chars for the current column.

@{b}MAXCOLWIDTH@{ub}
   Maximum number of chars for the current column.

@{b}PIXWIDTH@{ub}
   Wanted number of chars for the current column.

@{b}MINPIXWIDTH@{ub}
   Minimum number of chars for the current column.

@{b}MAXPIXWIDTH@{ub}
   Maximum number of chars for the current column.

Note: You will have as many columns in your list as
      entries in the format string (i.e. number of
      commas + 1). Empty entries, e.g. with a format
      string of ",,,," are perfectly ok.

MINPIXWIDTH, MAXPIXWIDTH, MINCOLWIDTH, MAXCOLWIDTH,
MINWIDTH and MAXWIDTH will not be used if PIXWIDTH,
or COLWIDTH is used.

Only one of PIXWIDTH, COLWIDTH and WEIGHT will be
used, the first find in this order.
Biggest of MINPIXWIDTH, MINCOLWIDTH and MINWIDTH.
Smallest of MAXPIXWIDTH, MAXCOLWIDTH and MAXWIDTH.
If the min is bigger than the max the min will be used.

You should used PIX ones only for columns with images,
and COL ones when you want to be sure to get as many
chars you want.

All chars/images will be drawn for the last column
always, you should specify some width for it anyway
as it will be used for centered and right aligned texts !

Default values : WEIGHT=100, MINWIDTH=10, MAXWIDTH=1000.
(using MUIA_List_Format instead MUIA_NList_Format, default
weight will be -1, like the default of List object)

Use MINWIDTH=0 if you don't use PIXWIDTH or COLWIDTH and
don't want any min value.

If you want to use WEIGHT values as percentage of the list
width, just choose them to have their total egual to 100.

WEIGHT = -1 mean that you want the column to have
the width of the largest entry's column contents.
MINWIDTH = -1 have the same meaning as for WEIGHT but for
the min value.
Be aware that it takes long time to do that when there
are many entries since this need a call to the dislpayhook,
parse and find real length of all entries.
Anyway using such stuff for one or more column has the
same overhead.

If BAR or TBAR is set, DELTA will be increase by 2.

Format
------

   Whenever MUI prints strings, they may contain some special
character sequences defining format, color and style of the text.

'\n'	   Start a new line. With this character you can e.g. create
         multi line buttons.

ESC -    Disable text engine, following chars will be printed
         without further parsing.

ESC u    Set the soft style to underline.

ESC b    Set the soft style to bold.

ESC i    Set the soft style to italic.

ESC n    Set the soft style back to normal.

ESC <n>  Use pen number n (2..9) as front pen. n must be a valid
         DrawInfo pen as specified in "intuition/screens.h".

ESC c    Center current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC r    Right justify current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC l    Left justify current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC j    Justify left and right current line. only at beginning.

ESC P[]  Use default front pen.

ESC T    Draw horizontal line on top of the entry for the column.

ESC C    Draw horizontal line centered in the entry for the column.

ESC B    Draw horizontal line on bottom of the entry for the column

ESC E    Draw horizontal line centered in the entry for the column,
         but only on the left and right of the line contents.

   You can define this variable for every group.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Add some horizontal bars:
       ( PINT.ArticleFormat "P=\33r D=8, D=8, D=8, P=\33r D=8 BAR, D=8 MIW=0 BAR, D=8 BAR, D=8, MIW=0 MAW=100" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "P=\33r D=8, D=8, D=8, P=\33r D=8 BAR, D=8 MIW=0 BAR, D=8 BAR, D=8, MIW=0 MAW=100"

@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_ATTRIB" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_ATTRIB"
@Next "CF_UMS_DISC"
@Prev "CF_UMS_ARTFOR"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Attributes[...]
====================

   With this variable you can set for each group a default value for the
Attribute string-gadget in the Mail- and Post-Windows.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     In Mailfolder "PostMaster" use another alias:
       ( PINT.Attributes.Mail.PostMaster "Alias postmaster" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Mail-Fenster" Link "WI_MAIL"} @{"Post-Fenster" Link "WI_POST"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_DISC" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_DISC"
@Next "CF_UMS_DISP"
@Prev "CF_UMS_ATTRIB"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.DisableCatchup[...]
========================

   With this variable you can disable the Catchup-function in different
groups.  This is quite nice in the mail or in mailfolders to avoid
unwanted catchups.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Disable Catchup for the complete Mail groups:
       ( PINT.DisableCatchup.Mail Yes )

@{b}Default:@{ub} No


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_DISP" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_DISP"
@Next "CF_UMS_BEEP"
@Prev "CF_UMS_DISC"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Display[...]
=================

    @{b}Normal@{ub}
          The @{b}Floadtext.mui@{ub} is used.

    @{b}Textfield@{ub}
          @{b}textfield.gadget@{ub} is used.

    @{b}Mailtext@{ub}
          @{b}Mailtext.mcc@{ub} is used.

@{b}Default:@{ub} Normal


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_BEEP" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_BEEP"
@Next "CF_UMS_RAW"
@Prev "CF_UMS_DISP"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.DisplayBeep[...]
=====================

   If a message that is displayed in the message window is addressed to you,
a DisplayBeep will be executed. You can define this variable for every group.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Beep in all comp.sys#? groups:
       ( PINT.DisplayBeep.comp.sys#? Yes )

@{b}Default:@{ub} NO


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_RAW" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_RAW"
@Next "CF_UMS_DIST"
@Prev "CF_UMS_BEEP"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.DisplayRaw[...]
====================

   Disable attribute processing. You can define this variable for every group.

@{b}NOTE!@{ub} This variable is only available if the @{"Mailtext.mcc" Link "CF_UMS_DISP"} is used.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Display all mails without attribute processing:
       ( PINT.DisplayRaw.Mail YES )

@{b}Default:@{ub} NO

@EndNode


@Node "CF_UMS_DIST" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_DIST"
@Next "CF_UMS_EDITOR"
@Prev "CF_UMS_RAW"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Dist[...]
==============

   This variable is used to set the distribution for locally created
messages.  Some networks use this field for restricting the
distribution of a message.  This variable must match the "Distribution"
field of one of the exporters.  You can define this variable for every
single group.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Distribution for all groups:
       ( PINT.Dist "world" )
     
     No distribution for FidoNet:
       ( PINT.Dist.fidonet  "" )
     
     Distribution for "de.#?":
       ( PINT.Dist.de "de" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_EDITOR" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_EDITOR"
@Next "CF_UMS_FORTUNE"
@Prev "CF_UMS_DIST"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Editor[...]
================

   With this variable you can decide which editor should be used to
write messages for the specific group. The editor must @{i}not@{ui} detach from
CLI.  You can define an editor for every single group.

   @{i}Attention:@{ui} You should use a standard Amiga text editor. It has to
terminate lines with a LF ($0A). PINT does @{i}not@{ui} perform any changes
to the file before writing it into the messagebase.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Configuration for CygnusEd:
       ( PINT.Editor "ED -sticky" )
     
     Configuration for TurboText:
       ( PINT.Editor "TTX WAIT" )
     
     Configuration for XDME:
       ( PINT.Editor "XDME -n" )
     
     Configuration only for "de.#?":
       ( PINT.Editor.de "MyFavouriteEditor -floattextoff" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "$EDITOR" (Environment Variable)

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"EDITOR" Link "CF_ENV_EDITOR"} @{"PINT.Stack" Link "CF_UMS_STACK"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_FORTUNE" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_FORTUNE"
@Next "CF_UMS_FWDHD"
@Prev "CF_UMS_EDITOR"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Fortune[...]
=================

   Some people like to add nice short messages so called "fortune
cookies" to the bottom of their messages. These messages are usually
created by so called "fortune cookie programs". With this variable you
can specify a program whose standard output is appended to the bottom
of the message right behind the signature.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Simply append the output for all FidoNet groups:
       ( PINT.Fortune.fidonet "Echo *\\"A stupid cookie*\\"" )
     
     Calling a real fortune cookie program:
       ( PINT.Fortune.de "Bin:Cookie CookieTexts:StarTrek.cookies" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_FWDHD" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_FWDHD"
@Next "CF_UMS_FUPTO"
@Prev "CF_UMS_FORTUNE"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.ForwardHeader[...]
=======================

   You can use this variable to define the header for forwarded
messages. This variable's name can be expanded by a full or partial
group name. These are the supported format identifiers:

     "%%" for the per cent sign.
     "%a" for the address of the original sender.
     "%d" for the creation date and time of the original message.
     "%f" for the firstname of the original sender.
     "%g" for the group of the orignal message.
     "%i" for the MessageID of the original message.
     "%n" for the name of the original sender.
     "%s" for the subject of the original sender.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Universal ForwardHeader for all messages:
       ( PINT.ForwardHeader
           "* Forwarded from : \\"%g\\"\\n"
           "* Originally by: %n (%a)\\n\\n"
       )
     
     ForwardHeader for NetMail:
       ( PINT.ForwardHeader.Mail
           "\\tHello,\\n"
           "\\n"
           "here is a forwarded message from %n\\n"
           "\\n"
       )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "* Forwarded from newsgroup \\"%g\\"\\n"                 "*
Originally from: %n (%a)\\n"                 "* Original date: %d\\n"


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_FUPTO" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_FUPTO"
@Next "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"
@Prev "CF_UMS_FWDHD"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.FupTo[...]
===============

   Certain networks have binary groups in which it is not wanted to post
discussion messages. Mostly there is a special discussion group. With
this variable you can set the replygroup for messages posted into one
of the binary groups. This feature is not supported by all networks.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Followups in de.alt.binaries.amigaos should go to de.alt.binaries.amigaos.d:
       ( PINT.FupTo.de.alt.binaries.amigaos "de.alt.binaries.amigaos.d" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (Followups to the group of the original message)

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.AnswerTo" Link "CF_UMS_ANSTO"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_GRPFOR" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_GRPFOR"
@Next "CF_UMS_HEADERS"
@Prev "CF_UMS_FUPTO"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.GroupFormat[...]
=======================

   Using this variable you can configure the listview in the 
Group window.

   To define how many columns should be displayed and how they 
should be formatted, you specify a format string.

   This format string must contain one entry for each column
you want to see. Entries are seperated by commas, one entry is 
parsed via dos.library/ReadArgs().

   The template for a single entry looks like this:

DELTA=D/N,PREPARSE=P/K,COL=C/N,BAR/S,TBAR/S,
WEIGHT=W/N,MINWIDTH=MIW/N,MAXWIDTH=MAW/N,
COLWIDTH=CW/N,MINCOLWIDTH=MICW/N,MAXCOLWIDTH=MACW/N,
PIXWIDTH=PW/N,MINPIXWIDTH=MIPW/N,MAXPIXWIDTH=MAPW/N

@{b}DELTA@{ub}
   Space in pixel between this column and the next.
   the last displayed column ignores this setting.
   Defaults to 4.

@{b}PREPARSE@{ub}
   A preparse string for this column.

@{b}COL@{ub}
   This value adjusts the number of the current column.
   Defaults to current entry number (0,1,...)

@{b}BAR@{ub}
   Will draw a vertical bar between this and the next column.

@{b}WEIGHT@{ub}
   The weight of the column. As for MUI's group.

@{b}MINWIDTH@{ub}
   Minimum percentage of the list width for the current column.

@{b}MAXWIDTH@{ub}
   Maximum percentage of the list width for the current column.

@{b}TBAR@{ub}
   Will draw a vertical bar between this and the next column
   but only in the title (ignored if BAR is set).

@{b}COLWIDTH@{ub}
   Wanted number of chars for the current column.
   You will get as PIXWIDTH with number*font_with.
   Possibly more than number chars will fit in the
   column if you use proportional font, anyway you
   are sure than number non italic chars will fit.

@{b}MINCOLWIDTH@{ub}
   Minimum number of chars for the current column.

@{b}MAXCOLWIDTH@{ub}
   Maximum number of chars for the current column.

@{b}PIXWIDTH@{ub}
   Wanted number of chars for the current column.

@{b}MINPIXWIDTH@{ub}
   Minimum number of chars for the current column.

@{b}MAXPIXWIDTH@{ub}
   Maximum number of chars for the current column.

Note: You will have as many columns in your list as
      entries in the format string (i.e. number of
      commas + 1). Empty entries, e.g. with a format
      string of ",,,," are perfectly ok.

MINPIXWIDTH, MAXPIXWIDTH, MINCOLWIDTH, MAXCOLWIDTH,
MINWIDTH and MAXWIDTH will not be used if PIXWIDTH,
or COLWIDTH is used.

Only one of PIXWIDTH, COLWIDTH and WEIGHT will be
used, the first find in this order.
Biggest of MINPIXWIDTH, MINCOLWIDTH and MINWIDTH.
Smallest of MAXPIXWIDTH, MAXCOLWIDTH and MAXWIDTH.
If the min is bigger than the max the min will be used.

You should used PIX ones only for columns with images,
and COL ones when you want to be sure to get as many
chars you want.

All chars/images will be drawn for the last column
always, you should specify some width for it anyway
as it will be used for centered and right aligned texts !

Default values : WEIGHT=100, MINWIDTH=10, MAXWIDTH=1000.
(using MUIA_List_Format instead MUIA_NList_Format, default
weight will be -1, like the default of List object)

Use MINWIDTH=0 if you don't use PIXWIDTH or COLWIDTH and
don't want any min value.

If you want to use WEIGHT values as percentage of the list
width, just choose them to have their total egual to 100.

WEIGHT = -1 mean that you want the column to have
the width of the largest entry's column contents.
MINWIDTH = -1 have the same meaning as for WEIGHT but for
the min value.
Be aware that it takes long time to do that when there
are many entries since this need a call to the dislpayhook,
parse and find real length of all entries.
Anyway using such stuff for one or more column has the
same overhead.

If BAR or TBAR is set, DELTA will be increase by 2.

Format
------

   Whenever MUI prints strings, they may contain some special
character sequences defining format, color and style of the text.

'\n'	   Start a new line. With this character you can e.g. create
         multi line buttons.

ESC -    Disable text engine, following chars will be printed
         without further parsing.

ESC u    Set the soft style to underline.

ESC b    Set the soft style to bold.

ESC i    Set the soft style to italic.

ESC n    Set the soft style back to normal.

ESC <n>  Use pen number n (2..9) as front pen. n must be a valid
         DrawInfo pen as specified in "intuition/screens.h".

ESC c    Center current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC r    Right justify current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC l    Left justify current (and following) line(s).
         This sequence is only valid at the beginning of a
         string or after a newline character.

ESC j    Justify left and right current line. only at beginning.

ESC P[]  Use default front pen.

ESC T    Draw horizontal line on top of the entry for the column.

ESC C    Draw horizontal line centered in the entry for the column.

ESC B    Draw horizontal line on bottom of the entry for the column

ESC E    Draw horizontal line centered in the entry for the column,
         but only on the left and right of the line contents.

   You can define this variable for every group.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Don't use any horizontal bars:
       ( PINT.GroupFormat ""MIW=0 MAW=100 D=16, P=\33r D=16 W=0, P=\33r W=0" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""MIW=0 MAW=100 D=16 BAR, BAR P=\33r D=16 W=0, P=\33r W=0"

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.ArticleFormat" Link "CG_UMS_ARTFOR"}

@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_HEADERS" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_HEADERS"
@Next "CF_UMS_NEWSRDR"
@Prev "CF_UMS_GRPFOR"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Headers[...]
=================

   Additional to the message text UMS stores data (normally not very
interesting for the user) which is hidden by PINT. If you always
want to see these informations use this variable.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Message header always on:
       ( PINT.Headers On )
     
     Message header off for all FidoNet groups:
       ( PINT.Headers.fidonet Off )
     
     Message header on for "fidonet.AMIGA.GER":
       ( PINT.Headers.fidonet.AMIGA.GER On )

@{b}Default:@{ub} Off

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Header on/off" Link "WI_MSG_CYCLE"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_NEWSRDR" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_NEWSRDR"
@Next "CF_UMS_ORG"
@Prev "CF_UMS_HEADERS"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Newsreader[...]
====================

   Normally PINT writes its name into the UMS newsreader field
which is supported by most of exports. The field is set to the name
"PINT" followed by the version number and the compilation date. In
some networks or groups these kind of information is not very welcome
so you can switch it off.  You can define this variable for every
group. All values except "No" will be considered as yes.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     newsreader field off:
       ( PINT.Newsreader No )
     
     newsreader field for all FidoNet groups on:
       ( PINT.Newsreader.fidonet Yes )

@{b}Default:@{ub} Yes


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_ORG" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_ORG"
@Next "CF_UMS_QCHARS"
@Prev "CF_UMS_NEWSRDR"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Organization[...]
======================

   This variable is the initial value for your organization (called
"Origin" in FidoNet). You can define a special organization for every
group.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Organization for all groups:
       ( PINT.Organization "Amiga User Group Universität Paderborn" )
     
     Organization for NetMail (private Mail):
       ( PINT.Organization.Mail "Where no mails have gone before" )
     
     Organization for "fidonet.AMIPROG.GER":
       ( PINT.Organization.fidonet.AMIPROG.GER
           "Allgemeiner Müsli und Obst Klub Stuttgart"
       )
     
     Organization for "de.#?":
       ( PINT.Organization.de = "private Amiga site" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (No organization).


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QCHARS" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QCHARS"
@Next "CF_UMS_QELINES"
@Prev "CF_UMS_ORG"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuoteChars[...]
====================

   Normally the quoted parts of a message are introduced with a certain
character. PINT can be configured to recognize such quotes and to
highlight the quoted text. PINT checks the first eight characters
of each line for the characters defined in this variable and highlights
the line if it finds one of them. You can define this variable for
every group.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Recognize ">" and "|":
       ( PINT.QuoteChars ">|" )
     
     Recognize only ">" in FidoNet groups:
       ( PINT.QuoteChars.fidonet ">" )
     
     Recognize "%", ">" and "|" in German UseNet groups:
       ( PINT.QuoteChars.de "%>|" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (No lines are highlighted)


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QELINES" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QELINES"
@Next "CF_UMS_QHEADER"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QCHARS"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuoteEmptyLines[...]
=========================

   Use this variable if you don't want to quote empty lines. You can define 
this variable for every group. All values except "No" will be considered as 
yes.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Don't quote empty lines in FidoNet groups:
       ( PINT.QuoteEmptyLines.fidonet NO )

@{b}Default:@{ub} Yes

@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QHEADER" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QHEADER"
@Next "CF_UMS_QMODE"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QELINES"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuoteHeader[...]
=====================

   You can use this variable to define the header for quoted messages.
This variable's name can be expanded by a full or partial group name.
These are the supported format identifiers:

     "%%" for the per cent sign.
     "%a" for the addresse of the original sender.
     "%d" for the creation date and time of the original message.
     "%f" for the firstname of the original sender.
     "%g" for the group of the orignal message.
     "%i" for the MessageID of the original message.
     "%N" for the firstname or "You" for mail.
     "%n" for the name of the original sender.
     "%s" for the subject of the original sender.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Universal QuoteHeader for all messages:
       ( PINT.QuoteHeader "%n wrote in article <%i> about %s this:" )
     
     QuoteHeader for NetMail:
       ( PINT.QuoteHeader.Mail
           "\\tHello %f !\\n"
           "\\n"
           "You wrote in '%g' this:\\n"
       )
     
     QuoteHeader like XRN's one for "de.#?":
       ( PINT.QuoteHeader.de "In article <%i>, wrote %n <%a>:" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "%n wrote in %g about \\"%s\\":"


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QMODE" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QMODE"
@Next "CF_UMS_QPFIX"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QHEADER"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuoteMode[...]
===================

   This variable presets the quote mode of PINT. This variable's
name can be expanded by a full or partial group name.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Quote without reflow in general:
       ( PINT.QuoteMode "normal" )
     
     Use reflow in FidoNet groups:
       ( PINT.QuoteMode.fidonet "reflow" )
     
     Ask in "comp.sys.amiga.programmer":
       ( PINT.QuoteMode.comp.sys.amiga.programmer "" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QPFIX" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QPFIX"
@Next "CF_UMS_QSIG"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QMODE"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuotePostFix[...]
=====================

   If the contents isn't empty this string will be appended after
the previous quotestring on all lines that already have been quoted. No
QuoteString will be added on these lines (if the string isn't empty).

   This variable's name can be expanded by a full or partial group name.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     QuoteString with intitials:
       ( PINT.QuoteString "%i> " )

     Normal QuotePostFix:
       ( PINT.QuotePostFix "> " )

Will quote the following text like this:

--
MH> This is a quoted text

This text has never been quoted....
--

--
MH>> This is a quoted text

DR> This text has never been quoted....
--

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.QuoteString" Link "CF_UMS_QSTRING"} @{"PINT.QuoteEmptyLines" Link "CF_UMS_QELINES"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QSIG" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QSIG"
@Next "CF_UMS_QSTRING"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QPFIX"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuoteSignature[...]
========================

   This variable controls whether signatures should be quoted or not. This 
variable's name can be expanded by a full or partial group name.

"--", "---" or "-- " on a own line is interpreted as a signature start.



This is the messagebody.

--

 /This is the signature part



@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Allways quote signatures:
       ( PINT.QuoteSignature YES )

@{b}Default:@{ub} NO


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QSTRING" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QSTRING"
@Next "CF_UMS_QWIDTH"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QSIG"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuoteString[...]
=====================

   This variable defines the string which will precede lines of quoted
text.  This variable's name can be expanded by a full or partial group
name.

@{b}You can use special format characters in this string:@{ub}

     "%%" for the per cent sign
     "%i" for the initials of the author of the original message.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Simple QuoteString:
       ( PINT.QuoteString "> " )
     
     QuoteString with intitials:
       ( PINT.QuoteString "%i> " )
     
     QuoteString for NetMail:
       ( PINT.QuoteString.Mail "You: " )
     
     QuoteString like XRN's one for "de.#?":
       ( PINT.QuoteString.de "|> " )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "> "

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.QuotePostFix" Link "CF_UMS_QPFIX"} @{"PINT.QuoteEmptyLines" Link "CF_UMS_QELINES"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_QWIDTH" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_QWIDTH"
@Next "CF_UMS_REPLPRE"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QSTRING"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.QuoteWidth[...]
====================

   Because a quoted part of text shouldn't be reformatted you are able
to configure the width beyond which the text shall be wrapped. This
variable's name can be expanded by a full or partial group name.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Universal width (for all groups):
       ( PINT.QuoteWidth 78 )
     
     Width for "de.#?":
       ( PINT.QuoteWidth.de 75 )
     
     Width for the group "fidonet.AMIGA.GER":
       ( PINT.QuoteWidth.fidonet.AMIGA.GER 73 )

@{b}Default:@{ub} 75


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_REPLPRE" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_REPLPRE"
@Next "CF_UMS_REPLYTO"
@Prev "CF_UMS_QWIDTH"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.ReplyPrefix[...]
=====================

   Many news systems add a leading "Re:" to the subject of answers to
messages.  In UseNet this behaviour is not required but suggested. With
this variable you are able to switch off the creation of such prefixes.
An already existing prefix is recognized and discarded.

   This variable can be defined for every particular group. All values
but "No" are considered as yes.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Never create a Reply-Prefix:
       ( PINT.ReplyPrefix No )
     
     But for FidoNet:
       ( PINT.ReplyPrefix.fidonet Yes )
     
     But not in fidonet.AMIGA.GER:
       ( PINT.ReplyPrefix.fidonet.AMIGA.GER No )

@{b}Default:@{ub} Yes


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_REPLYTO" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_REPLYTO"
@Next "CF_UMS_SAVEDRW"
@Prev "CF_UMS_REPLPRE"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.ReplyTo[...]
=================

   If you want replies of your messages to go to another address you
can use this variable to define a reply address for each group or
network. The used format is "[Name,]Address". If no name is supplied
PINT creates one from the address. E.g. "corwin@pixar.owl.de" is
converted to "corwin,corwin@pixar.owl.de".

   This feature will not work with all networks.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Answers to messages in "de.#?":
       ( PINT.ReplyTo.de "nd95mho@Student.HGS.SE" )
     
     Answers to messages NetMail in folder "NetBSD":
       ( PINT.ReplyTo.Mail.NetBSD "David Rydh, dary@lindesign.se" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (No reply address is created)


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SAVEDRW" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SAVEDRW"
@Next "CF_UMS_SAVEMARK"
@Prev "CF_UMS_REPLYTO"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.SaveDrawer[...]
====================

   PINT is able to save the current message into a file. For this
purpose a filerequester is opened for getting the path and filename.
This variable defines the default directory for this file requester.
This variable's name can be expanded by a full or partial group name.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Directory for saving messages:
       ( PINT.SaveDrawer "UMS:Text" )
     
     Directory for saving Netmail:
       ( PINT.SaveDrawer.Mail "UMS:Text/Mail" )
     
     Directory for saving FidoNet messages:
       ( PINT.SaveDrawer.fidonet "UMS:Text/Fido" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (The current directory)

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.SaveMark" Link "CF_UMS_SAVEMARK"} @{"PINT.SaveNameType" Link "CF_UMS_SAVNT"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SAVEMARK" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SAVEMARK"
@Next "CF_UMS_SAVNT"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SAVEDRW"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.SaveMark[...]
==================

   Multiple messages saved by PINT can be seperated by a mark
which can be defined with this variable. This variable's name can be
expanded by a full or partial group name.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Universal configuration:
       ( PINT.SaveMark "-------cut-------\\n" )
     
     Nothing appended to Netmail:
       ( PINT.SaveMark.Mail "" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (No mark)

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.SaveDrawer" Link "CF_UMS_SAVEDRW"} @{"PINT.SaveNameType" Link "CF_UMS_SAVNT"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SAVNT" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SAVNT"
@Next "CF_UMS_SIGNATURE"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SAVEMARK"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.SaveNameType[...]
======================

   Normally PINT uses the group name of a public message or the
sender of a Netmail as default for the filename for saving a message.
With this variable you can define another criteria for each group.

@{b}The following values are recognized:@{ub}

     "Subject"  The subject is used as filename.
     "Group"    The group name is used as filename.
     "FromName" The name of the sender is used as filename.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Use the subject for FidoNet groups:
       ( PINT.SaveNameType.fidonet Subject )
     
     In "de.#?" the name of the sender:
       ( PINT.SaveNameType.de FromName )
     
     The subject for Netmail:
       ( PINT.SaveNameType.Mail Subject )

@{b}Default:@{ub} ""

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.SaveMark" Link "CF_UMS_SAVEMARK"} @{"PINT.SaveDrawer" Link "CF_UMS_SAVEDRW"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SIGNATURE" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SIGNATURE"
@Next "CF_UMS_SORT"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SAVNT"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Signature[...]
===================

   This variable defines the signature written under your messages. You
can define different signatures for each group of course.

   @{i}Attention:@{ui} Signatures are not welcome everywhere.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Signature for all groups:
       ( PINT.Signature
           "\\n"
           "Magnus Heino\\n"
           "nd95mho@Student.HGS.SE\\n"
       )
     
     Signature for NetMail:
       ( PINT.Signature.Mail
           "\\n"
           "See you later...\\n"
           "\\t\\tDavid Rydh\\n"
       )
     
     Signature for the group "fidonet.AMIGA.GER":
       ( PINT.Signature.fidonet.AMIGA.GER
           "\\n"
           "-MS-\\n"
       )
     
     Signature for "comp.sys.amiga.#?":
       ( PINT.Signature.comp.sys.amiga "\\nMarc Barett\\n" )

@{b}Default:@{ub} "" (No signature).


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_SORT" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_SORT"
@Next "CF_UMS_WARP"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SIGNATURE"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Sort[...]
==============

   There are three methods to sort the articles in the article window.
You can define the sort method for each group or network.

@{b}The following methods are supported:@{ub}

     "Date"      Sort list by creationdate.
     "MsgNum"    Sort list by message number.
     "ReplyLink" Sort list by reply linking.
     "Subject"   Sort list by subject.

@{b}Examples:@{ub}

     Sort by reply linking:
       ( PINT.Sort ReplyLink )
     
     Sort Netmail by message number:
       ( PINT.Sort.Mail MsgNum )

@{b}Default:@{ub} MsgNum

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Sort Menu" Link "WI_READ_MENU"}


@EndNode

@Node "CF_UMS_WRAP" "PINT.guide/CF_UMS_WRAP"
@Next "CF_ENV_EDITOR"
@Prev "CF_UMS_SORT"
@Toc "IN_CONFIG"

PINT.Wordwrap[...]
==================

   Disable wordwrap. You can define this variable for every group.

@{b}NOTE!@{ub} This variable is only available if the @{"Mailtext.mcc" Link "CF_UMS_DISP"} is used.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     Never use wordwrap on mail
       ( PINT.Wordwrap.Mail NO )

@{b}Default:@{ub} YES


@EndNode

@Node "IN_STARTUP" "PINT.guide/IN_STARTUP"
@Next "IN_INTRO"
@Prev "IN_CONFIG"
@Toc "Main"

Starting PINT
=============

Starting from a shell
---------------------

   If you start PINT from a shell you may supply the following
arguments:

@{b}NAME@{ub}
     The name of the UMS user.

@{b}PASSWORD@{ub}
     The password for this user. The password is case sensitive. If you
     supply "." as password PINT will not attempt to login but
     open the @{"Login window" Link "WI_LOGIN"} and request the password.

@{b}SERVER/K@{ub}
     The UMS server to use. You must use the keyword "SERVER" in front
     of this argument.

@{b}MAIL/S@{ub}
     PINT opens a Mail Window from which you can start to write a
     mail. After the Mail Window is closed, PINT quits.

@{b}POST/S@{ub}
     PINT opens a Post Window from which you can start to write a
     news. After the Post Window is closed, PINT quits.

@{b}SEARCH/S@{ub}
     PINT opens the global search window from which you can search
     messages.  After the Message- and ArticleWindows are closed,
     PINT quits.

@{b}TO/K@{ub}
     With this option you can predefine the receiver of a message if
     you use the Mail- or Post-options.

@{b}SUBJECT/K@{ub}
     With this option you can predefine the subject of a message if you
     use the Mail- or Post-options.

@{b}Example:@{ub}

     1> PINT "Stefan Stuntz" Nose

Starting from the Workbench
---------------------------

   PINT can be started by double clicking on its Workbench icon.
In this case PINT will read the following tooltypes from the icon:

@{b}NAME@{ub}
     The name of the UMS user.

@{b}PASSWORD@{ub}
     The password for this user. The password is case sensetiv. If you
     supply "." as password PINT will not attempt to login but
     open the @{"Login window" Link "WI_LOGIN"} and request the password.

@{b}SERVER@{ub}
     The UMS-Server to use.

@{b}MAIL@{ub}
     PINT opens a Mail Window from which you can start to write a
     mail. After the Mail Window is closed, PINT quits.

@{b}POST@{ub}
     PINT opens a Post Window from which you can start to write a
     news. After the Post Window is closed, PINT quits.

@{b}SEARCH/S@{ub}
     PINT opens the global search window from which you can search
     messages.  After the Message- and ArticleWindows are closed,
     PINT quits.

@{b}Example for the ToolTypes:@{ub}

     NAME=Martin Horneffer
     PASSWORD=.
     SERVER=default

   If PINT is started without any arguments it will open its
@{"Login window" Link "WI_LOGIN"} and ask for a user, password and optional server to enable
a manual login into the UMS messagebase.

   If you only supply a username PINT will try to login without
password. If this attempt fails it will open the @{"Login window" Link "WI_LOGIN"} and
activate the password gadget.

   It's currently not possible to start PINT iconified. 

@EndNode

@Node "WI_LOGIN" "PINT.guide/WI_LOGIN"
@Next "WI_GROUP"
@Prev "WI_BOOK"
@Toc "Main"

The Login Window
================

   To be able to use PINT you have to log into an account of the
UMS messagebase.

   This can be done by supplying arguments if you start PINT from
a shell or ToolTypes in its icon if you use the Workbench (see also
@{"Starting PINT" Link "IN_STARTUP"}).

   If you didn't supply a username or if the login attempt was not
successful the login window is opened.

String Gadgets
--------------

@{b}Name@{ub}
     Use this stringgadget to enter the account name for the UMS
     messagebase.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'N'

@{b}Password@{ub}
     Use this stringgadget to enter the password for the account.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'P'

@{b}Server@{ub}
     Use this stringgadget to enter the server to connect to.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'S'

   After the "Ok" button is pressed PINT tries to login with the
supplied account name and password. If the attempt fails a requester is
opened and you can decide to change the inputs and retry.

   After the "Cancel" button is pressed PINT closes the Login
Window. If you activated this function by the menu item @{"ReLogin..." Link "WI_GRP_MENU"}
PINT will continue to work under the old account. Otherwise
PINT will terminate.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GROUP" "PINT.guide/WI_GROUP"
@Next "WI_ARTICLE"
@Prev "WI_LOGIN"
@Toc "Main"

The Group Window
================

   The Group Window is the main window of PINT. If you close it
PINT will terminate. You can select groups from here or start a
global search through the whole message base.

   The cycle gadget @{"ScanMode1" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"} is not usable if the configuration
variable @{"PINT.FastScan" Link "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"} is set to "Yes".

The Group Window has the following control items:


 @{" List          " Link "WI_GRP_LIST"}		Group Selection
 @{" Buttons       " Link "WI_GRP_BUTTON"}		Buttons in the Group Window
 @{" Cycle Gadgets " Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"}		ScanMode1 and ScanMode2 cycle gadgets
 @{" Menus         " Link "WI_GRP_MENU"}		Menus attached to the Group Window


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GRP_LIST" "PINT.guide/WI_GRP_LIST"
@Next "WI_GRP_BUTTON"
@Prev "WI_GRP_MENU"
@Toc "WI_GROUP"

Group Selection
---------------

   This listview is used to display all groups in alphabetical order.
Behind every group you will see two numbers. The first one shows the
number of new messages, the second one the total number of the messages
fulfilling the criteria of @{"ScanMode1" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"}. The content of this listview is
directly affected by the settings of the cycle gadgets in the group
window.

   Groups containing new messages to the current user are highlighted
in the list.

   PINT supports so called "mail folders" to be able to divide personal mail. 
These folders are shown at the top of the list labeled "Mail: <Foldername>".

   @{i}Attention:@{ui} Folders are only supported if the folder field (15) is
marked as index field in the "ums.config". Otherwise personal mail can
not be sorted into different folders.

   The listview may be controlled via mouse or keyboard. After a double
click on an entry the selected group will be scanned. After the scan
has been completed the @{"Article Window" Link "WI_ARTICLE"} will appear showing all the
messages in the selected group.

   Controlling the listview with the keyboard is this easy, too. Just
use the cursor keys and @{b}SPACE@{ub} to (de)select groups and @{b}RETURN@{ub} to enter a
group.

   The group selection supports multiselect. Use @{"Read..." Link "WI_GROUP"} to read one
group after the other.

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Read..." Link "WI_GROUP"} @{"ScanMode1" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"} @{"ScanMode2" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"}


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GRP_BUTTON" "PINT.guide/WI_GRP_BUTTON"
@Next "WI_GRP_CYCLE"
@Prev "WI_GRP_LIST"
@Toc "WI_GROUP"

Buttons
-------

@{b}Mail...@{ub}
     If you press this button the @{"Mail Window" Link "WI_MAIL"} is opened for writing a
     Netmail.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'M' or AMIGA-'M'

@{b}Post...@{ub}
     If you press this button the @{"Post Window" Link "WI_POST"} is opened for writing a
     public message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'P' or AMIGA-'P'

@{b}Read...@{ub}
     If you select this button the first selected group is scanned and
     displayed.  After you left this group the next selected group is
     scanned. If you abort the scan process the complete function will
     be aborted.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'R' or AMIGA-'R'

@{b}Rescan@{ub}
     If you select this button PINT will update its group list.
     This function is only necessary if another program imported
     messages or manipulated the UMS messagebase. Because this function
     performs only a partial scan it is quite fast.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'E' or AMIGA-'E'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GRP_CYCLE" "PINT.guide/WI_GRP_CYCLE"
@Next "WI_GRP_MENU"
@Prev "WI_GRP_BUTTON"
@Toc "WI_GROUP"

Cycle Gadgets
-------------

ScanMode1
.........

   UMS supports multiple flags for selecting messages. Use this gadget
to tell PINT which flag to check for.

@{b}Normal@{ub}
     All messages are scanned.

@{b}Selected@{ub}
     All pre-selected messages are scanned. These message were probably
     selected by another tool because the user want to read them in any
     case.

@{b}PostPoned@{ub}
     All postponed messages are scanned. Postponed messages were marked
     by the user to be read later. They will me marked as new if
     PINT is started again.

@{b}Archived@{ub}
     All archived messages are scanned. The user normally marked these
     messages because he considers them as very important. These
     messages normally will not be expired.

@{b}Junked@{ub}
     All junked messages are scanned. These messages were probably
     filtered by an external tool because the user doesn't want to see
     them. If he wants to take a look on what is filtered he can use
     this mode. In this case the menu item @{"Scan junked" Link "WI_GRP_MENU"} is ignored.

@{b}Parked@{ub}
     All  parked messages are scanned. These messages will not be
     exported until the parked flag is cleard. This feature is useful
     for writing bugreports or feature requests so you can collect the
     features or bugs in a messages and don't send it until your
     message is complete.

@{b}FromUser@{ub}
     All messages addressed to the current user are scanned.

@{b}ToUser@{ub}
     All messages written by the current user are scanned.

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.ScanMode1" Link "CF_UMS_SCANMODE1"} @{"PINT.FastScan" Link "CF_UMS_FASTSCAN"}

ScanMode2
.........

   With this gadget you can decide whether you want to see only new
messages or old ones, too, and how much of them.

@{b}New@{ub}
     Only new messages are scanned.

@{b}All@{ub}
     All messages are scanned.

@{b}Last XX@{ub}
     The last XX messages in a group are scanned.

   @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'A'

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.ScanMode2" Link "CF_UMS_SCANMODE2"}


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GRP_MENU" "PINT.guide/WI_GRP_MENU"
@Next "WI_GRP_LIST"
@Prev "WI_GRP_CYCLE"
@Toc "WI_GROUP"

Menus
-----

Project Menu
............

@{b}ReLogin...@{ub}
     This menu item will open the @{"Login Window" Link "WI_LOGIN"}.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'L'

@{b}About...@{ub}
     This menu item will open the information requester. You'll find
     the current user and server displayed in it.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'?'

@{b}About MUI...@{ub}
     This menu item will open the standard MUI about window.

@{b}Iconify...@{ub}
     This menu item will close all windows and iconify PINT.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'I'

@{b}Quit...@{ub}
     If you select this menu item PINT will be terminated. If
     there are still changes which should be applied to the messagebase
     PINT will let you confirm this decision.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'Q'

Groups Menu
...........

@{b}Read...@{ub}
     See button @{"Read..." Link "WI_GRP_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Catch up@{ub}
     With this menu item you can mark all messages in all selected
     groups as read.  This way you can get off lots of uninteresting
     messages very fast.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'C'

@{b}Select Pattern...@{ub}
     With this menu item you can select groups by a AmigaDOS patterns.
     You are prompted for pattern and have the options to select,
     deselect or toggle all matching groups.

     Use 'Cancel' to abort this function.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'T'

@{b}Select all@{ub}
     With this menu item you can select all groups. This is e.g.
     usefull if you want to use "Catchup" or "Read...".

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'+'

@{b}Unselect all@{ub}
     With this menu item you can deselect all groups.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'-'

@{b}Rescan@{ub}
     See button @{"Rescan" Link "WI_GRP_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Rescan all@{ub}
     Under some rare circumstances it is necessary to recreate the
     group list from scratch. This can be done with this menu item.

     A complete rescan is necessary if messages are put into a folder
     while PINT is running or if the commands under
     @{"PINT.Startup" Link "CF_UMS_STARTUP"} and @{"PINT.StartupNew" Link "CF_UMS_STARTUPN"} should be started again.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'A'

Messages Menu
.............

@{b}Search...@{ub}
     After selecting this menu item the @{"Search Window" Link "WI_GLOBSEARCH"} is opend.  You
     can use it to search for messages in the whole message base.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'S'

@{b}Mail...@{ub}
     See button @{"Mail..." Link "WI_GRP_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Post...@{ub}
     See button @{"Post..." Link "WI_GRP_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Contact Support...@{ub}
     Write a message with a bug report or a question to the
     @{"PINT Support" Link "BI_AUTHORS"}.

Preferences Menu
................

@{b}Scan junked@{ub}
     Normally PINT will ignore messages junked by a filter
     program. If you want to see them anway switch on this menu item.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'J'

@{b}Groupfilter active@{ub}
     You can use the configuration variable @{"PINT.Groups" Link "CF_UMS_GROUPS"} to select
     the groups you wish to see. If you want to see all groups
     temporarily switch this menu item off.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'G'

@{b}Edit address book...@{ub}
     Open the address book edit window.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'B'

@{b}Edit preferences...@{ub}
     Open the precerence edit window.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'O'

@{b}MUI...@{ub}
     Open the MUI preference window.

Cache Menu
..........

@{b}Create@{ub}
     With this menu item you can create a cache for the grouplist and
     the folders.  It will be used in the Mail-, Post- and global
     SearchWindows for the group and folder lists. While creating this
     cache PINT uses the groups listed in @{"PINT.Groups" Link "CF_UMS_GROUPS"}.

     @{i}WARNING: UMSServer up to version 11.31 (inclusive) have a bug in
     writing very big configuration variables. Start the UMSServer with
     a very large stack (about 100kB, depends on the number of news
     groups you have) if you want to use this option. Otherwise your
     ums.config will be destroyed!@{ui}

@{b}Delete@{ub}
     With this menu item you can delete the cache.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_ARTICLE" "PINT.guide/WI_ARTICLE"
@Next "WI_MESSAGE"
@Prev "WI_GROUP"
@Toc "Main"

The Article Window
==================

   The Article Window is used to display a list of the messages
available for reading. You can directly select them here.

The Article Window has the following control items:


 @{" Text gadgets " Link "WI_ART_TEXT"}			Gadgets for viewing information
 @{" List         " Link "WI_ART_LIST"}			Article Selection
 @{" Buttons      " Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}			Buttons in the Article Window
 @{" Menus        " Link "WI_READ_MENU"}			Menus attached to the Article Window

   If you close the Article Window all changes are written back to the
UMS messagebase as if you selected @{"Update" Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_ART_TEXT" "PINT.guide/WI_ART_TEXT"
@Next "WI_ART_LIST"
@Prev "WI_ART_BUTTON"
@Toc "WI_ARTICLE"

Text Gadgets
------------

@{b}Group@{ub}
     This gadget shows the current group. If the messagelist is
     assembled from different groups (e.g. after a Global Search) it
     will show "Misc".

@{b}Info@{ub}
     In this gadget you'll find useful information like the number of
     messages or how many of them were affected by the last flag
     change.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_ART_LIST" "PINT.guide/WI_ART_LIST"
@Next "WI_ART_BUTTON"
@Prev "WI_ART_TEXT"
@Toc "WI_ARTICLE"

messagelist
-----------

   All available messages are shown in this listview. These listview
consists of four columns:

@{b}Message Number@{ub}
     The number of the message in the UMS messagebase.

@{b}Message Flags@{ub}
     The most important message flags are display in the messagelist:

    @{b}'N'@{ub}
          The message is marked as new and has not been read yet.

    @{b}'P'@{ub}
          The message is postponed. It will be shown again later.

    @{b}'A'@{ub}
          The message is archived so it will never be expired.

    @{b}'S'@{ub}
          The message is selected, it's probably important.

          Messaged marked as new and selected will automatically be
          selected in the messagelist.

    @{b}'J'@{ub}
          The message is junked. You don't want to see it normally.

    @{b}'D'@{ub}
          The message is marked as deleted. If you leave the Article
          Window with "Catch up" or "Update" it will be deleted from
          the UMS messagebase.

    @{b}'X'@{ub}
          The message is marked as expired. It will be deleted while
          the next cleanup of the UMS messagebase.

    @{b}'E'@{ub}
          The message is marked a exported. It was read by an exporter
          or is readable for a local user.

    @{b}'P'@{ub}
          The message is parked. This means that it will not be
          exported until this flag is cleared.

@{b}Date@{ub}
     This column displays the date that the message arrived to your 
     system.

@{b}Size@{ub}
     In this column the size of the message in bytes is displayed. This
     information may not be 100% exact because the private data stored
     by the importer is included, for softlinks it's completely wrong.
     This not a bug in PINT but a feature of the UMS-Server.

@{b}Sender@{ub}
     In this column the sender of the message is displayed. If the
     message is addressed to the current user this name is highlighted.

@{b}Receiver@{ub}
     In this column the receiver of the message is displayed. If the
     message is addressed to the current user the senders is set to bold.

@{b}Subject@{ub}
     In this column you can see the subject of the message. A "+" in
     front of the subject marks an answer to the previous message. A
     ">" marks another answer to the same message.

   After a doubleclick on a message the @{"Message Window" Link "WI_MESSAGE"} is opened for
the particular message. You can also select a message via keyboard and
press @{b}RETURN@{ub} to look at it.

   Another way is to select multiple messages and read them by pressing
@{"Read Selected" Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_ART_BUTTON" "PINT.guide/WI_ART_BUTTON"
@Next "WI_ART_TEXT"
@Prev "WI_ART_LIST"
@Toc "WI_ARTICLE"

Buttons
-------

@{b}Write...@{ub}
     If you select this gadget in a Netmail group the @{"Mail Window" Link "WI_MAIL"} is
     opened. If you use it in a normal news group the @{"Post Window" Link "WI_POST"} is
     opened. This way it's easy to write a message in the current group.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'W' or AMIGA-'W'

@{b}Read selected@{ub}
     This function will remove all unselected messages from the
     messagelist. This way you can preselect messages for read. To get
     the complete messagelist back use "Show All".

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'R' or AMIGA-'H'

@{b}Show All@{ub}
     This function is the opposite of "Read selected". Use it to get
     back the hidden messages.

     All messages visible in the reduced messagelist will be selected
     in the complete messagelist. So you can switch fast between both
     states.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'S' or AMIGA-'I'

@{b}Catch up@{ub}
     After selecting this gadget the Article Window is closed, all
     messages are marked as old and PINT returns to the
     @{"Group Window" Link "WI_GROUP"}.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'C' or AMIGA-'C'

@{b}Update@{ub}
     After selecting this gadget the Article Window is closed, all
     changes done by the user are written back to the UMS messagebase
     and PINT returns to the @{"Group Window" Link "WI_GROUP"}.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'U' or AMIGA-'U'

@{b}No Change@{ub}
     After selecting this gadget the Article Window is closed and
     PINT returns to the @{"Group Window" Link "WI_GROUP"}. No changes are written to
     the UMS messagebase.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'N' or AMIGA-'N'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MESSAGE" "PINT.guide/WI_MESSAGE"
@Next "WI_MAIL"
@Prev "WI_ARTICLE"
@Toc "Main"

The Message Window
==================

   The Message Window is used for displaying messages. Multiple kind of
informations are shown and you have the possibility to manipulate the
flags of the current message.

The Message Window has these control items:


 @{" Text Gadgets  " Link "WI_MSG_TEXT"}		Gadgets for viewing author, subject, etc.
 @{" List          " Link "WI_MSG_LIST"}		The message text
 @{" Buttons       " Link "WI_MSG_BUTTON"}		Buttons in the Message Window
 @{" Cycle Gadgets " Link "WI_MSG_CYCLE"}		Switch headers on or off
 @{" Menus         " Link "WI_READ_MENU"}		Menus attached to the Message Window

Keyboard shortcuts
------------------

   The Message Window has several keyboard shortcuts to make easy
control possible.

@{b}SPACE@{ub}
     Jump to the next message.

@{b}RETURN@{ub}
     Jump to the message under the cursor of the messagelist in the
     Article Window.

@{b}Cursor Left/Right@{ub}
     Jump to the next/previous message.

@{b}SHIFT Cursor Left/Right@{ub}
     Jump to the parent/child of the current message.

@{b}ALT Cursor Left/Right@{ub}
     Jump to the left/right brother of the current message.

@{b}DEL@{ub}
     Mark the current message as deleted.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MSG_TEXT" "PINT.guide/WI_MSG_TEXT"
@Next "WI_MSG_LIST"
@Prev "WI_MSG_CYCLE"
@Toc "WI_MESSAGE"

Text Gadgets
------------

@{b}From@{ub}
     This gadget shows the author of the message.

@{b}Date@{ub}
     This gadget shows the date that the message was written.

@{b}To@{ub}
     This gadget shows the receiver of the message. For a public
     messages without a receiver but with a father message the author
     of the father message is shown.

@{b}Date@{ub}
     This gadget shows the date that the message was received.

@{b}Subject@{ub}
     You will find the subject of the message in this gadget.

@{b}Group@{ub}
     You will find the group of the message in the window title.

@{b}Flags@{ub}
     
     The most important message flags are displayed in the messagelist:

     Click on them to toggle.

    @{b}'N'@{ub}
          The message is marked as new and has not been read yet.

    @{b}'P'@{ub}
          The message is postponed. It will be shown again later.

    @{b}'A'@{ub}
          The message is archived so it will never be expired.

    @{b}'S'@{ub}
          The message is selected, it's probably important.

          Messaged marked as new and selected will automatically be
          selected in the messagelist.

    @{b}'J'@{ub}
          The message is junked. You don't want to see it normally.

    @{b}'D'@{ub}
          The message is marked as deleted. If you leave the Article
          Window with "Catch up" or "Update" it will be deleted from
          the UMS messagebase.

    @{b}'X'@{ub}
          The message is marked as expired. It will be deleted while
          the next cleanup of the UMS messagebase.

    @{b}'E'@{ub}
          The message is marked a exported. It was read by an exporter
          or is readable for a local user.

         This flag can't be toggled.

    @{b}'P'@{ub}
          The message is parked. This means that it will not be
          exported until this flag is cleared.

@EndNode

@Node "WI_MSG_LIST" "PINT.guide/WI_MSG_LIST"
@Next "WI_MSG_BUTTON"
@Prev "WI_MSG_TEXT"
@Toc "WI_MESSAGE"

Listview for the Message Text
-----------------------------

   This listview is used to view the message text. Normally you only
see the text itself. If you switch the headers on you will find some
additionally information e.g. sender's and receiver's address, group
and message flags at the top and the comment at the bottom. The comment
is used by importers to store network specific data.

   PINT supports highlighting quoted text. You can configure the
characters for recognizing it.

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.QuoteChars" Link "CF_UMS_QCHARS"}


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MSG_BUTTON" "PINT.guide/WI_MSG_BUTTON"
@Next "WI_MSG_CYCLE"
@Prev "WI_MSG_LIST"
@Toc "WI_MESSAGE"

Buttons
-------

@{b}Reply...@{ub}
     After selecting this button the @{"Mail Window" Link "WI_MAIL"} is opened prepared for
     writing a reply to the current message. All string gadgets of the
     window will be initialized.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'R' or AMIGA-'R'

@{b}FollowUp...@{ub}
     After selecting this button the @{"Post Window" Link "WI_POST"} is opened prepared for
     writing a followup to the current message. All string gadgets of
     the window will be initialized.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'F' or AMIGA-'F'

@{b}Edit...@{ub}
     This button is used for editing own messages. After selecting it
     the @{"Mail Window" Link "WI_MAIL"} is opened in case of Netmail, the @{"Post Window" Link "WI_POST"} for
     public message. After you changed the message it will be written
     into the UMS message base and the old one will be deleted.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'E'

@{b}Save...@{ub}
     This button is used for saving messages. For this purpose a
     standard file requester is opened to let you choose the filename.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'S'

@{b}Delete@{ub}
     Mark the current message as deleted. It will be deleted from the
     UMS messagebase as soon as you select "Catch up" or "Update".

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'D' or DEL

@{b}Previous@{ub}
     Jump to the previous message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'V' or Cursor-Left

@{b}Next@{ub}
     Jump to the next message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'N' or Cursor-Right

@{b}- (ChainUp)@{ub}
     Jump to the parent of the current message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} '-' or SHIFT-Cursor-Left

@{b}< (ChainLeft)@{ub}
     Jump to the left brother of the current message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} '<' or ALT-Cursor-Left

@{b}> (ChainRight)@{ub}
     Jump to the right brother of the current message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} '>' or ALT-Cursor-Right

@{b}+ (ChainDown)@{ub}
     Jump to the first child of the current message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} '+' or SHIFT-Cursor-Right


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MSG_CYCLE" "PINT.guide/WI_MSG_CYCLE"
@Next "WI_MSG_TEXT"
@Prev "WI_MSG_BUTTON"
@Toc "WI_MESSAGE"

Cycle Gadgets
-------------

@{b}Header on/off@{ub}
     With this gadget you can decide wether PINT shall show the
     headers and comment of the message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'H'

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.Headers" Link "CF_UMS_HEADERS"}


@EndNode

@Node "WI_READ_MENU" "PINT.guide/WI_READ_MENU"
@Next "WI_READ_MENU"
@Prev "WI_READ_MENU"
@Toc "WI_ARTICLE"

Menus
-----

Project
.......

@{b}Catch up@{ub}
     See button @{"Catch up" Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Update@{ub}
     See button @{"Update" Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}.

@{b}No Change@{ub}
     See button @{"No Change" Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}.

@{b}About@{ub}
     See menu @{"About" Link "WI_GRP_MENU"}.

@{b}Quit...@{ub}
     See menu @{"Quit" Link "WI_GRP_MENU"}.

Messagelist
...........

@{b}Sort@{ub}
    @{b}by Date@{ub}
          If you select this menu item the messagelist will be sorted
          by the creation date of the messages.

          @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMGA-'7'

    @{b}by MsgNumber@{ub}
          If you select this menu item the messagelist will be sorted
          by the number of the messages in the UMS messagebase. This is
          normally the order in which they were written in the
          messagebase.

          @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'1'

    @{b}by ReplyLink@{ub}
          If you select this menu item the messagelist will be sorted
          by reply linking.  In this order messages will appear below
          their parent message. The second criteria for sorting is the
          subject.

          @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'2'

    @{b}by Subject@{ub}
          If you select this menu item the messagelist will be sorted
          alphabetically by the subject, prefixes like "Re:" are
          ignored.

          @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'3'

@{b}ScanMode@{ub}
     Select which messages you want to display in this group. This works 
     the same as the group window @{"cyclegadget" Link "WI_GRP_CYCLE"}.

@{b}Rescan@{ub}
     Rescan the current group.

@{b}Search...@{ub}
     This meny item brings up the {"Global search window" Link "WI_GLOBSEARCH"}.
     It can be used to select or deselect messages by AmigaDOS patterns.

@{b}Select pattern...@{ub}
     This menu item opens the @{"Select Window" Link "WI_SELECT"}. It can be used to select
     or deselect messages by AmigaDOS patterns.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'S'

@{b}Select all@{ub}
     Select all messages in the messagelist.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'+'

@{b}Unselect all@{ub}
     Unselect all messages in the messagelist.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'-'

@{b}Read selected@{ub}
     See button @{"Read selected" Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}

@{b}Show all@{ub}
     See button @{"Show all" Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}

@{b}Hide@{ub}
    @{b}same Author@{ub}
          With this menu item you can remove all messages from the
          message list which were written by the same author as the
          current one. This is a kind of temporary filter for removing
          uninteresting messages.

          If you call this function from the Article Window all
          messages by the authors of all selected messages are filtered.

          @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'4'

    @{b}same Subject@{ub}
          With this menu item you can remove all messages from the
          message list which have the same subject as the current one.
          This is a kind of temporary filter for removing uninteresting
          messages.

          If you call this function from the Article Window all
          messages with a subject like the one of the selected message
          are filtered.

          @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'5'

@{b}Set, Unset and Toggle flags@{ub}
     With these three menus you are able to set, unset and toggle flags
     for messages.

     If you use these menu items in the Article Window the changes are
     applied to all selected messages. If no message is selected they
     are applied to the message under the cursor.

     If you use these menu items in the Message Window the changes are
     applied to the current message.

     PINT supports the manipulation of these flags:

    @{b}mark@{ub}
          Mark message.

    @{b}archive@{ub}
          Message will be archived, it will not be expired.

    @{b}postpone@{ub}
          Message will be postponed, it will be marked as new if
          PINT is started again.

    @{b}junk@{ub}
          Message will be junked, it will not be scanned again.

    @{b}old@{ub}
          Message will be marked as old.

    @{b}delete@{ub}
          Message will be deleted.

    @{b}expire@{ub}
          Message will be expired, it will removed with the next
          cleanup of UMS messagebase.

    @{b}park@{ub}
          The message will be parked. This means that it will not be
          exported until this flag is cleared.

Messages
........

@{b}Write...@{ub}
     See button @{"Write..." Link "WI_ART_BUTTON"}

@{b}Reply...@{ub}
     See button @{"Reply..." Link "WI_MSG_BUTTON"}

@{b}Direct Reply...@{ub}
     If this item is selected PINT will open the @{"Mailwindow" Link "WI_MAIL"} and
     the real author of the current message will be inserted into the
     To-field.  This means that an eventually existent Reply-To header
     and the variable @{"PINT.AnswerTo" Link "CF_UMS_ANSTO"} will be ignored.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'6'

@{b}FollowUp...@{ub}
     See button @{"FollowUp..." Link "WI_MSG_BUTTON"}

@{b}Move to folder...@{ub}
     After you select this menu item a requester is opened and you are
     prompted for the name of a folder. The message will be moved into
     the folder you enter. This function is only available for Netmail.

     If you call this function from the Article Window all selected
     messages are moved to the specified folder.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'G'

@{b}Forward as Mail...@{ub}
     If you select this menu item the @{"Mail Window" Link "WI_MAIL"} is opened prepared to
     forward the message via Netmail. This way you can send a mail you
     received to somebody else. You can edit the message before it is
     written to the UMS messagebase.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'K'

@{b}Forward as News...@{ub}
     If you select this menu item the @{"Post Window" Link "WI_POST"} is opened prepared to
     forward this message to another newsgroup. This way you can
     crostpost a public message. You can edit the message before it is
     written to the UMS messagebase.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'L'

@{b}Add to address book...@{ub}
     With this menu item you can add the author of the current message
     to the @{"Adressbook" Link "WI_BOOK"}. For this purpose the @{"Comment Requester" Link "WI_REQCOMMENT"} is
     opened. If the variable @{"PINT.Book" Link "CF_UMS_BOOK"} points to an ARexx script
     this ARexx script will be called with the parameters "ADD
     <Name>,<Address>,<Comment>".

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'B'

@{b}Edit...@{ub}
     See button @{"Edit" Link "WI_MSG_BUTTON"}

@{b}Save as...@{ub}
     See button @{"Save..." Link "WI_MSG_BUTTON"}

@{b}Save to clipboard...@{ub}
     This menu item can be used to save the current message to the
     clipboard. You will be prompted for the clipboard unit to use.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'Y'

@{b}Save attached file...@{ub}
     If a file is attached to a message, this file can be save with
     this menu item.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'T'

@{b}Print...@{ub}
     This menu item can be used to print out the current message. You
     will be prompted for the name of the printer device.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'Z'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_SELECT" "PINT.guide/WI_SELECT"
@Next "WI_SELECT"
@Prev "WI_SELECT"
@Toc "WI_READ_MENU"

The Selection Window
====================

   With the selection function you can select messages in the Article
List by an AmigaDOS pattern.

Stringgadgets
-------------

@{b}FromName@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the sender.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'F'

@{b}ToName@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the receiver.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'T'

@{b}Subject@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the subject.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'S'

The flags of all messages matching all three patterns are modified.

Use "Cancel" to abort this function.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_REQCOMMENT" "PINT.guide/WI_REQCOMMENT"
@Next "WI_REQCOMMENT"
@Prev "WI_REQCOMMENT"
@Toc "WI_READ_MENU"

Comment Requester
=================

   The Comment Requester is used to modify an entry before writing it
to the address book. It has the following control items:

Stringgadgets
-------------

@{b}Name@{ub}
     Name of the user to add to the address book.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'N'

@{b}Address@{ub}
     Address of the user to add to the address book.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'A'

@{b}Comment@{ub}
     Comment for the new entry in the address book.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'M'

     @{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Adressbook" Link "WI_BOOK"}

   Select "Ok" to confirm the input or "Cancel" to abort.

   If the person is already present in the address book the new address
is added to the entry. If even the address is present nothing is added.

   @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'B'

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Address Book" Link "WI_BOOK"}


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MAIL" "PINT.guide/WI_MAIL"
@Next "WI_POST"
@Prev "WI_MESSAGE"
@Toc "Main"

The Mail Window
===============

   In this window you can prepare all information for writing a
Netmail. For this purpose it has the following control items:


 @{" List           " Link "WI_MAIL_LIST"}		Receivers of the message
 @{" String Gadgets " Link "WI_MAIL_STR"}		String gadgets in the Mail Window
 @{" Buttons        " Link "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"}		Edit, Send, Cancel...
 @{" Menus          " Link "WI_MAIL_MENU"}		Menus attached to the Mail Window


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MAIL_LIST" "PINT.guide/WI_MAIL_LIST"
@Next "WI_MAIL_STR"
@Prev "WI_MAIL_MENU"
@Toc "WI_MAIL"

Receiverlist
------------

   Use this list to enter the receivers of the message.

   If you perform a doubleclick on an entry it will be moved to the top
of the list.

   Below the list you will find a stringgadget for entering a receiver
directly.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MAIL_STR" "PINT.guide/WI_MAIL_STR"
@Next "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"
@Prev "WI_MAIL_LIST"
@Toc "WI_MAIL"

String Gadgets
--------------

@{b}Subject@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the subject for the message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'U'

@{b}Folder@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the folder for the new message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'F'

@{b}Organization@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the organization for the message. In
     FidoNet this information is used for the "Origin".

     You can use the UMS configuration variable @{"PINT.Organization" Link "CF_UMS_ORG"}
     to define an organization for every group.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'O'

@{b}Attributes@{ub}
     UMS supports attributes for messages. For possible values see the
     UMS documentation and the documentations of the exporters.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'I'

@{b}Reply-To@{ub}
     Sometimes you may redirect the answers to a mail to another
     address. Use this gadget to enter the reply address.

     This feature will not work with all networks.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'R'

@{b}Distribution@{ub}
     This variable is used to set the distribution for locally created
     messages.  Some networks use this field for restricting the
     distribution of a message.  Use this sting gadget to enter the
     distribution.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'T'

@{b}File@{ub}
     In this string gadget you can set the name of a file which is
     attached to the message. If an exporter supports this feature and
     how it handles the attached file see the documentation of the
     corresponding exporter.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'L'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MAIL_BUTTON" "PINT.guide/WI_MAIL_BUTTON"
@Next "WI_MAIL_MENU"
@Prev "WI_MAIL_STR"
@Toc "WI_MAIL"

Buttons
-------

@{b}Add@{ub}
     If you select this button the active entry of the receiverlist is
     deactivated and the string gadget for entering the receiver is
     activated. This way you are able to add another receiver in an
     easy way.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'A'

@{b}Del@{ub}
     If you select this button the active entry is removed from the
     receiverlist.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'D'

@{b}Popup Address book@{ub}
     After selecting this button the @{"Address Book" Link "WI_BOOK"} is opened.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'P' or AMIGA-'P'

     @{b}See also:@{ub} @{"Address Book" Link "WI_BOOK"}

@{b}Edit...@{ub}
     If you select this button PINT invokes @{"your text editor" Link "CF_UMS_EDITOR"}.
     PINT will ask if you want to quote the current message if you
     invoked the Mail- or Post-Window via reply or followup functions.
     There are two possibilities to quote a message. First you can use
     the "quote with reflow" function and PINT reformats the
     quoted message completely. This can result in an completely
     destroyed format of the message if it was a source code or
     something similar. If this is the case you can use the normal
     quoting so PINT won't reformat anything.

     If the signature of the original message starts with "\\n-- \\n"
     PINT ignores all lines after this special mark for the
     quoting.

     If you call the editor the first time the signature will be
     appended to the message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'E'

@{b}Send@{ub}
     After you select this button PINT tries to write the message
     to the UMS messagebase. If this attempt is not successful an error
     requester will appear.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'S'

@{b}Park@{ub}
     After you select this button PINT tries to write the message
     to the UMS messagebase. If this attempt is not successful an error
     requester will appear.  Furthermore the parked flag of the message
     will be set. This means that the message won't be exported until
     the parked flag is cleared.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'K'

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     After you select this button the Mail Window will be closed and
     the message will not be discarded.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'C'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_MAIL_MENU" "PINT.guide/WI_MAIL_MENU"
@Next "WI_MAIL_LIST"
@Prev "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"
@Toc "WI_MAIL"

Menus
-----

@{b}Address book...@{ub}
     The @{"Address Book" Link "WI_BOOK"} is opened.

@{b}Crash@{ub}
     In FidoNet it's possible to send messages directly to a system
     without routing via other systems.

     If you select this menu item the "Crash" attribute is set.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} AMIGA-'C'

@{b}Receipt-request@{ub}
     In FidoNet it's possible to get a confirmation from the destination
     system when the netmail has reached there.

     If you select this menu item the "Receipt-request" attribute is set.

@{b}Audit-request@{ub}
     In FidoNet it's possible to get a confirmation from all systems that 
     a netmail has been routed through.

     If you select this menu item the "Audit-request" attribute is set.

@EndNode

@Node "WI_POST" "PINT.guide/WI_POST"
@Next "WI_GLOBSEARCH"
@Prev "WI_MAIL"
@Toc "Main"

The Post Window
===============

   In this window you can prepare all information for writing a public
message.  For this purpose it has the following control items:


 @{" List           " Link "WI_POST_LIST"}		Groups to post into
 @{" String Gadgets " Link "WI_POST_STR"}		String gadgets in the Post Window
 @{" Buttons        " Link "WI_POST_BUTTON"}		Edit, Send, Cancel...
 @{" Menus          " Link "WI_POST_MENU"}		Menus attached to the Post Window


@EndNode

@Node "WI_POST_LIST" "PINT.guide/WI_POST_LIST"
@Next "WI_POST_STR"
@Prev "WI_POST_MENU"
@Toc "WI_POST"

Grouplist
---------

   Use this list to enter the groups into which you want to write your
message.

   If you perform a doubleclick on a group it will be moved to the top
of the list and the settings for this group e.g. signature and
organization will be used.

   Below the list you will find a stringgadget for entering a group
directly.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_POST_STR" "PINT.guide/WI_POST_STR"
@Next "WI_POST_BUTTON"
@Prev "WI_POST_LIST"
@Toc "WI_POST"

String Gadgets
--------------

@{b}Subject@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the subject for the message.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'U'

@{b}ToName@{ub}
     Some networks support a receiver name for public message. Use this
     gadget to enter it.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'N'

@{b}Organization@{ub}
     See String Gadget @{"Organization" Link "WI_MAIL_STR"}.

@{b}Attributes@{ub}
     See String Gadget @{"Attributes" Link "WI_MAIL_STR"}.

@{b}Reply-To@{ub}
     See String Gadget @{"Reply-To" Link "WI_MAIL_STR"}.

@{b}FollowUp-To@{ub}
     Certain networks have binary groups in which it is not wanted to
     post discussion messages. Mostly there is a special discussion
     group. Use this gadget to enter the replygroup for messages posted
     into one of the binary groups. This feature is not supported by
     all networks.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'L'

@{b}Distribution@{ub}
     This variable is used to set the distribution for locally created
     messages.  Some networks use this field for restricting the
     distribution of a message.  Use this sting gadget to enter the
     distribution.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'T'

@{b}File@{ub}
     See String Gadget @{"File" Link "WI_MAIL_STR"}.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_POST_BUTTON" "PINT.guide/WI_POST_BUTTON"
@Next "WI_POST_MENU"
@Prev "WI_POST_STR"
@Toc "WI_POST"

Buttons
-------

@{b}Add@{ub}
     See button @{"Add" Link "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Dell@{ub}
     See button @{"Del" Link "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Popup Grouplist@{ub}
     After selecting this button the @{"Group Selection Window" Link "WI_GRPLST"} is opened.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'P' or AMIGA-'P'

@{b}Edit...@{ub}
     See button @{"Edit" Link "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Send@{ub}
     See button @{"Send" Link "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Park@{ub}
     See button @{"Park" Link "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"}.

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     See button @{"Cancel" Link "WI_MAIL_BUTTON"}.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_POST_MENU" "PINT.guide/WI_POST_MENU"
@Next "WI_POST_LIST"
@Prev "WI_POST_BUTTON"
@Toc "WI_POST"

Menus
-----

@{b}Grouplist...@{ub}
     The @{"Group Selection Window" Link "WI_GRPLST"} is opened.

@EndNode

@Node "WI_GRPLST" "PINT.guide/WI_GRPLST"
@Next "WI_GRPLST"
@Prev "WI_GRPLST"
@Toc "WI_POST_BUTTON"

The Group Selection Window
--------------------------

   In this window you can select one or more groups in which your
message will be posted.

@{b}Grouplist@{ub}
     You can select one or more groups in this listview. You can
     confirm your choice by performing a doubleclick on a group or
     pressing @{b}RETURN@{ub}.

   Select "Ok" to confirm or "Cancel" to abort.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GLOBSEARCH" "PINT.guide/WI_GLOBSEARCH"
@Next "WI_BOOK"
@Prev "WI_POST"
@Toc "Main"

Global Search Window
====================

   The Global Search Window is used for entering criteria for a global
search through the UMS messagebase. You can enter AmigaDOS patterns in
the string gadgets but if you use normal strings searching will be much
faster.

The Global Search Window has the following control items:


 @{" Buttons        " Link "WI_GLS_BUTTON"}		Buttons in the Global Search Window.
 @{" String Gadgets " Link "WI_GLS_STR"}		String gadgets in the Global Search Window.
 @{" Cycle Gadgets  " Link "WI_GLS_CYCLE"}		Cycle gadgets in the Global Search Window.
 @{" Slider Gadgets " Link "WI_GLS_SLIDER"}		Slider gadgets in the Global Search Window.
 @{" Flag Page      " Link "WI_GLS_FLAGS"}		Search for message flags.

This window is available from two menus:

Group window
------------

   All messages which match these criteria will be read from the UMS
messagebase and displayed in a messagelist. If the scan window is
closed while PINT is searching it will abort and all messages
found so far will be displayed.

Article window
--------------

   All messages which match these criteria will be read from the UMS
messagebase. This list of messages are then compared with the current
article list. The selected state for each matched message will be toggled.

@{b}NOTE!@{ub} Try to reduse the critera for searching as much as possible.
      Searching is done with ALL messages in the UMS messagebase matching 
      the search critera, even if they are not in the current articlelist.

@EndNode

@Node "WI_GLS_BUTTON" "PINT.guide/WI_GLS_BUTTON"
@Next "WI_GLS_STR"
@Prev "WI_GLS_FLAGS"
@Toc "WI_GLOBSEARCH"

Buttons
-------

@{b}Clear@{ub}
     If you select this button all gadgets of the visible group are
     reset to their initial value. The pages "Normal" and "Flags" have
     their own local cancel gadget.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'L'

   Select "Ok" to start the global search or "Cancel" to abort.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GLS_STR" "PINT.guide/WI_GLS_STR"
@Next "WI_GLS_CYCLE"
@Prev "WI_GLS_BUTTON"
@Toc "WI_GLOBSEARCH"

String Gadgets
--------------

@{b}FromName@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the sender's name.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'F'

@{b}FromAddress@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the sender's address.

     @{i}Attention:@{ui} In a standard UMS configuration FromAddr (2) is no index
     field. In this case searching for a sender's address will take a
     long time.  Read the documentation about the UMS configuration
     about how to change this.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'A'

@{b}ToName@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the receiver's name.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'T'

@{b}ToAddress@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the receiver's address.

     @{i}Attention:@{ui} In a standard UMS configuration ToAddr (4) is no index
     field. In this case searching for a receiver's address will take a
     long time.  Read the documentation about the UMS configuration
     about how to change this.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'D'

@{b}Subject@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the subject.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'S'

@{b}Group@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the group.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'G'

@{b}Folder@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the folder.

     @{i}Attention:@{ui} In a standard UMS configuration Folder (15) is no index
     field. In this case searching for a folder will take a long time.
     Read the documentation about the UMS configuration about how to
     change this.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'L'

@{b}Message-ID@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the message-id.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'M'

@{b}Text@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the pattern for the messagetext.
     Searching for the messagetext is very slow so use it rarely.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'X'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GLS_CYCLE" "PINT.guide/WI_GLS_CYCLE"
@Next "WI_GLS_SLIDER"
@Prev "WI_GLS_STR"
@Toc "WI_GLOBSEARCH"

Cycle Gadgets
-------------

@{b}Searchmode@{ub}
     Use this gadget to select the messages for the global search.

    @{b}All@{ub}
          All messages are examined.

    @{b}New@{ub}
          Only new messages are examined.

    @{b}Old@{ub}
          Only old messages are examined.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'E'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GLS_SLIDER" "PINT.guide/WI_GLS_SLIDER"
@Next "WI_GLS_FLAGS"
@Prev "WI_GLS_CYCLE"
@Toc "WI_GLOBSEARCH"

Slider Gadgets
--------------

@{b}Maximum age@{ub}
     Use this slider to select the maximum age of messages to be
     searched for. If the slider is set to 0 (zero) all messages will
     be searched. If you set the slider to 14 then only the messages
     arrived in the last 14 days are searched.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'U'


@EndNode

@Node "WI_GLS_FLAGS" "PINT.guide/WI_GLS_FLAGS"
@Next "WI_GLS_BUTTON"
@Prev "WI_GLS_SLIDER"
@Toc "WI_GLOBSEARCH"

Flags page
----------

   On this page it is possible to select which flags the messages
should have or should not have in the seach process. If you want to
search for all archived messages just change the cycle gadget of the
archived flag to "Set". Now PINT will only search for messages
which have the archived flag set.

   The following settings are possible:

@{b}Ignore@{ub}
     PINT will search for all messages regardless if the specific
     flag is set or not set.

@{b}Set@{ub}
     PINT will only search for messages which have the specific
     flag set.

@{b}Not set@{ub}
     PINT will only search for messages which have the specific
     flag not set.


@EndNode

@Node "WI_BOOK" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOK"
@Next "WI_BOOKEDIT"
@Prev "WI_GLOBSEARCH"
@Toc "Main"

The Addressbook
===============

   In this window it is possible to select one receiver for a Netmail.

Textgadget
----------

@{b}Comment@{ub}
     You can find the comment for the active addressbook entry here.

Addresslist
-----------

   You can select one entry in this list. In the left column you will see 
the names, in the right one the addresses. One name can have multiple 
addresses. By performing a doubleclick on an entry or pressing @{b}RETURN@{ub} 
you can confirm the input.

   Select "Ok" to use the selected entries or "Cancel" to abort.

@{b}See also:@{ub} @{"PINT.Book" Link "CF_UMS_BOOK"}


@EndNode

@Node "WI_BOOKEDIT" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOKEDIT"
@Next "WI_PREFSEDIT"
@Prev "WI_BOOK"
@Toc "Main"

The Address Book Editor
=======================

   The Address Book Editor is used for easy maintenance of the @{"adress book" Link "CF_UMS_BOOK"}.

   You can edit as many users/groups/lists as you want, at the same time. You can drag a
user from any editing window, and drop it into some other window.

The Address Book Editor has the following control items:

 @{" List           " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_LISTVIEW"}		List of all users, groups and lists.
 @{" Buttons        " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_BUTTONS"}		Buttons in the Address Book Editor.

@Endnode

@Node "WI_BOOKEDIT_LISTVIEW" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOKEDIT_LISTVIEW"
@Next ""
@Prev ""
@Toc "Main"

List of addresses
-----------------

   In this list you will find all users, groups and lists from your
Address book, PINT.Book

   If you perform a doubleclick on a groupnode, all users in this
group will be displayed. A doubleclick on a user- or listnode will
open that entry for editing.

@EndNode

@Node "WI_BOOKEDIT_BUTTONS" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOKEDIT_BUTTONS"
@Next ""
@Prev ""
@Toc "Main"

Buttons
-------

@{b}NewUser@{ub}
     Use this gadget to add a user to the address book.
     A user may have multiple addresses.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'U'

@{b}NewList@{ub}
     Add a list with several members to the address book.
     All members in the list will recieve a message sent to it.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'L'

@{b}NewGroup@{ub}
     Add a hiearchic group to the address book.
     Messages can't be sent to the group itself.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'G'

@{b}Edit@{ub}
     Edit the current entry in the list.

     This will open either of;

        @{"User Edit  " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER"}
        @{"List Edit  " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_LIST"}
        @{"Group Edit " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_GROUP"}

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'E'

@{b}Delete@{ub}
     Delete the current entry in the list. 
     This action is undoable (nothing will happen if you press Cancel).

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'D'

@{b}Sort@{ub}
     Sort all entries in the current group.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'S'

@{b}Ok@{ub}
     Save all changes to the addressbok-file.
  
     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'O'

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Close the window and discard all changes.

     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'C'

@EndNode

@Node "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOKEDIT_USER"
@Next ""
@Prev ""
@Toc "Main"

Edit User window
----------------

   This window is used to edit the data of a user in the address book.

 @{" List           " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_LISTVIEW"}		List of all addresses for the user
 @{" Buttons        " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_BUTTONS"}		Add, Delete...
 @{" String Gadgets " Link "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_STRING"}		String gadgets

@EndNode

@Node "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_LISTVIEW" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_LISTVIEW"
@Next ""
@Prev ""
@Toc "Main"

List of addresses
-----------------

   This list contains all addresses of the current user.

@EndNode

@Node "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_BUTTONS" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_BUTTONS"
@Next ""
@Prev ""
@Toc "Main"

Buttons
-------

@{b}Add@{ub}
     Add a new address to the user. 
     Specify the address in the gadget to the left.
  
     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'a'

@{b}Del@{ub}
     Delete the current address.
  
     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'D'

@{b}Ok@{ub}
     Close window and apply changes made to the user.
  
     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'O'

@{b}Cancel@{ub}
     Close window and discard changes made to the user.
  
     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'C'

@EndNode

@Node "WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_STRING" "PINT.guide/WI_BOOKEDIT_USER_STRING"
@Next ""
@Prev ""
@Toc "Main"

String gadgets
--------------

@{b}Name@{ub}
     Use this gadget to enter the name of the user.
  
     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'N'

@{b}Comment@{ub}
     Use this gadget for a comment to the user.
  
     @{i}Keyboard shortcut:@{ui} 'C'

@EndNode

